U.S. Navy.

30
00:02:31,518 --> 00:02:33,887
"Subject, retirement."

31
00:02:35,221 --> 00:02:39,692
<i>NARRATOR: 22 November, 1945.</i>

32
00:02:39,726 --> 00:02:44,664
<i>He was born in</i>
<i>Elizabeth, New Jersey,</i>
<i>62 years ago, this date.</i>

33
00:02:44,697 --> 00:02:50,904
<i>Graduated from the</i>
<i>United States Naval Academy</i>
<i>at Annapolis in 1904.</i>

34
00:02:50,937 --> 00:02:56,209
<i>There were 62 men</i>
<i>in his class.</i>
<i>Scholastically, he stood 43rd.</i>

35
00:02:57,377 --> 00:02:59,345
<i>His speech is salty.</i>

36
00:02:59,379 --> 00:03:03,016
<i>On his right shoulder</i>
<i>there is a tattooed anchor.</i>

37
00:03:03,049 --> 00:03:05,785
<i>He once owned a parrot.</i>

38
00:03:05,818 --> 00:03:10,390
<i>He wears the wings of a pilot</i>
<i>earned at the age of 52.</i>

39
00:03:10,423 --> 00:03:16,396
<i>He is a sailor who has always</i>
<i>been welcome on any ship</i>
<i>at any time in any ocean.</i>

40
00:03:19,132 --> 00:03:22,135
<i>He now goes to his cabin</i>
<i>where, tradition dictates,</i>

41
00:03:22,168 --> 00:03:25,939
<i>he will change</i>
<i>to civilian clothes before</i>
<i>he can take leave of his ship.</i>

42
00:03:25,972 --> 00:03:28,908
Everything's
ready, sir.
Thank you.

43
00:03:46,593 --> 00:03:51,564
<i>NARRATOR: Manuel Salvador</i>
<i>Jesus Marlvilla,</i>
<i>one of 17 children.</i>

44
00:03:51,598 --> 00:03:56,769
<i>Born on the island of Luzon,</i>
<i>28 years in</i>
<i>the United States Navy.</i>

45
00:03:56,803 --> 00:04:01,407
<i>Cheerfully and reverently</i>
<i>he has served his God,</i>
<i>his country and his Admiral.</i>

46
00:04:01,441 --> 00:04:03,443
<i>He too is retiring today.</i>

47
00:04:04,043 --> 00:04:06,079
Manuel.
Yes, sir.

48
00:04:06,112 --> 00:04:07,847
What are your plans?

49
00:04:07,880 --> 00:04:13,186
I'll go back to Luzon, sir.
My brother has a farm.
I'm invited to live there.

50
00:04:13,219 --> 00:04:16,723
That sounds peaceful.
Yes, sir.

51
00:04:19,492 --> 00:04:21,094
You may find it
too peaceful.

52
00:04:21,127 --> 00:04:22,629
If I do, sir,

53
00:04:22,662 --> 00:04:27,133
I have only to remember
the unpeaceful times
we have known.

54
00:04:27,166 --> 00:04:29,969
It was enough excitement
for one lifetime.

55
00:04:31,738 --> 00:04:34,307
Yeah, I guess so.

56
00:04:39,178 --> 00:04:40,813
Manuel?
Yes, sir.

57
00:04:42,815 --> 00:04:44,651
What do you remember
best?

58
00:04:44,684 --> 00:04:52,792
Sir, I can remember
the Gilbert Islands,
the Marshall Islands,

59
00:04:52,825 --> 00:04:59,032
the Tokyo raid, Kwajalein
and so many others,
their names I cannot remember.

60
00:05:01,334 --> 00:05:06,839
But the one that will
always stay clear in
my mind is Guadalcanal.

61
00:05:08,708 --> 00:05:11,878
<i>NARRATOR: 16 October, 1942.</i>

62
00:05:29,595 --> 00:05:33,399
What's our ETA
for Guadalcanal?
06:30.

63
00:05:41,074 --> 00:05:42,475
I've had it.

64
00:05:44,043 --> 00:05:46,279
You can't read it
if you can't see it.

65
00:05:46,312 --> 00:05:50,183
<i>NARRATOR: The Admiral's staff</i>
<i>recruited from his</i>
<i>former flagship</i>

66
00:05:50,216 --> 00:05:52,952
<i>the aircraft carrier,</i>
 Enterprise.

67
00:05:52,985 --> 00:05:55,555
<i>Captain Frank Enright,</i>
<i>Plans Officer.</i>

68
00:05:57,123 --> 00:05:59,826
<i>Captain Bill Bailey,</i>
<i>Operations Officer.</i>

69
00:06:01,394 --> 00:06:04,163
<i>Captain Horace Key,</i>
<i>Senior Flight Surgeon.</i>

70
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:13,539
<i>Lieutenant Commander</i>
<i>Andrew Jefferson Lowe III,</i>
<i>aide and pilot,</i>

71
00:06:13,573 --> 00:06:16,743
<i>an authority on the Civil War</i>
<i>and the Charleston.</i>

72
00:06:19,412 --> 00:06:20,546
(CLEARS THROAT)

73
00:06:20,580 --> 00:06:22,215
How we doing, Andy?

74
00:06:22,248 --> 00:06:25,284
We'll land before daylight,
if there's anything
to land on.

75
00:06:25,318 --> 00:06:29,055
Tokyo Express
has been shelling
Guadalcanal all night.

76
00:06:29,088 --> 00:06:32,792
They estimate 6,000 more
Japanese troops will land.

77
00:06:33,426 --> 00:06:34,761
Six thousand.

78
00:06:36,829 --> 00:06:40,133
Why couldn't the old man
have chosen someplace
else to inspect?

79
00:06:40,166 --> 00:06:43,803
Yeah, someplace
where they got some nurses
or some pretty girls.

80
00:06:44,270 --> 00:06:45,938
(ALL LAUGH)

81
00:06:45,972 --> 00:06:47,840
Probably on account
of you.

82
00:06:49,442 --> 00:06:50,710
Casanova.

83
00:06:52,111 --> 00:06:53,679
Old man asleep?

84
00:06:53,713 --> 00:06:55,515
Thanks to Doc.

85
00:06:55,548 --> 00:06:57,984
How'd you manage
that, Doc?

86
00:06:58,017 --> 00:06:59,952
With a great
big pill.

87
00:06:59,986 --> 00:07:03,589
You mean you got the
old man to take a pill?
Sure I did.

88
00:07:03,623 --> 00:07:05,491
No, I don't
believe it.

89
00:07:14,467 --> 00:07:15,835
(SHUSHING)

90
00:07:36,189 --> 00:07:39,125
He's out like a light.

91
00:07:39,158 --> 00:07:41,327
It's the first time
he's closed his eyes
since we left Pearl Harbor.

92
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:43,029
Yeah.

93
00:07:43,062 --> 00:07:46,799
Say, wouldn't this be
a good time to sneak in there
and give him his shots?

94
00:07:46,833 --> 00:07:48,034
He needs the sleep more.

95
00:07:48,067 --> 00:07:49,869
I thought you gave him
the shots last week?

96
00:07:49,902 --> 00:07:53,439
No, no. We came close,
but he got away again.

97
00:07:55,908 --> 00:08:00,913
I never seen a body so afraid
of a little old hypodermic
needle as the old man is.

98
00:08:02,849 --> 00:08:07,386
Well, you got him
to take a pill, that's
a major victory in itself.

99
00:08:07,420 --> 00:08:08,421
That's right.
Yeah.

100
00:08:10,389 --> 00:08:15,728
<i>NARRATOR: Yes, Guadalcanal</i>
<i>is the next scheduled stop</i>
<i>on their inspection tour.</i>

101
00:08:15,761 --> 00:08:18,197
<i>But the schedule</i>
<i>could be changed.</i>

102
00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:09,382
<i>The report of the sighting</i>
<i>of the aircraft</i>

103
00:09:09,415 --> 00:09:13,352
<i>starts on its way to</i>
<i>Japanese headquarters</i>
<i>on the island of Truk.</i>

104
00:09:16,088 --> 00:09:17,657
(TELEGRAPH BEEPING)

105
00:09:47,286 --> 00:09:51,457
<i>The underground message center</i>
<i>in the basement of</i>
<i>Japanese headquarters.</i>

106
00:09:51,490 --> 00:09:53,826
<i>The sighting report is handed</i>
<i>to a decoding officer</i>

107
00:09:53,859 --> 00:09:56,963
<i>who will see to it</i>
<i>that it is delivered</i>
<i>to the appropriate authority.</i>

108
00:09:58,965 --> 00:10:04,937
<i>Rear Admiral Jiro Kobe,</i>
<i>Chief of Staff under</i>
<i>Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto.</i>

109
00:10:04,971 --> 00:10:08,207
<i>He is putting the</i>
<i>final touches on a detailed</i>
<i>plan for the ceremony</i>

110
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:11,978
<i>that will take place when</i>
<i>the allies surrender</i>
<i>the island of Guadalcanal.</i>

111
00:10:12,011 --> 00:10:13,045
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

112
00:10:13,079 --> 00:10:14,080
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

113
00:10:19,652 --> 00:10:21,887
(KOBE SPEAKS JAPANESE)

114
00:10:21,921 --> 00:10:25,491
<i>NARRATOR: The decoding officer</i>
<i>feels that the message of the</i>
<i>sighting is important enough</i>

115
00:10:25,524 --> 00:10:29,061
<i>to bring to the attention of</i>
<i>the Chief of Staff at once.</i>

116
00:10:35,101 --> 00:10:36,969
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

117
00:10:37,003 --> 00:10:39,805
<i>NARRATOR: Admiral Kobe is</i>
<i>a little annoyed at</i>
<i>the officer for bothering him</i>

118
00:10:39,839 --> 00:10:42,975
<i>with what he considers</i>
<i>a routine matter.</i>

119
00:10:43,009 --> 00:10:44,677
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

120
00:10:53,519 --> 00:10:55,187
(INTERCOM BUZZING)

121
00:10:57,423 --> 00:10:59,792
<i>(MAN SPEAKS JAPANESE</i>
<i>ON INTERCOM)</i>

122
00:11:04,063 --> 00:11:07,767
<i>NARRATOR: In spite of the fact</i>
<i>that the message appears</i>
<i>to be of little importance,</i>

123
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:10,336
<i>it is still</i>
<i>a classified document.</i>

124
00:11:10,369 --> 00:11:14,674
<i>And Admiral Kobe,</i>
<i>a very careful man,</i>
<i>does not leave it on his desk.</i>

125
00:11:14,707 --> 00:11:16,475
<i>He takes it with him.</i>

126
00:11:35,995 --> 00:11:38,364
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

127
00:11:38,397 --> 00:11:42,568
<i>NARRATOR: The gentleman</i>
<i>you are about to meet</i>
<i>is Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto,</i>

128
00:11:42,601 --> 00:11:45,571
<i>Commander-in-Chief of the</i>
<i>Combined Japanese Fleet.</i>

129
00:11:45,604 --> 00:11:47,640
(YAMAMOTO SPEAKS JAPANESE)

130
00:11:54,580 --> 00:12:00,586
<i>NARRATOR: Born of seafaring</i>
<i>stock on an island north of</i>
<i>Japan, April 4th, 1884.</i>

131
00:12:00,619 --> 00:12:04,957
<i>He graduated from</i>
<i>the Japanese Naval Academy</i>
<i>in 1904.</i>

132
00:12:04,990 --> 00:12:08,394
<i>Americans who knew him when</i>
<i>he was a naval attache</i>
<i>in Washington, D.C.</i>

133
00:12:08,427 --> 00:12:11,163
<i>remember him</i>
<i>as an excellent poker player.</i>

134
00:12:11,197 --> 00:12:13,632
<i>He was especially good</i>
<i>at bluffing.</i>

135
00:12:14,333 --> 00:12:15,968
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

136
00:12:17,203 --> 00:12:18,771
<i>NARRATOR: Admiral Yamamoto</i>
<i>asks Kobe</i>

137
00:12:18,804 --> 00:12:22,908
<i>for his latest estimate</i>
<i>of the enemy situation</i>
<i>on Guadalcanal.</i>

138
00:12:22,942 --> 00:12:25,744
<i>Kobe tells him that</i>
<i>Japanese naval</i>
<i>and air bombardments</i>

139
00:12:25,778 --> 00:12:30,182
<i>have put almost all</i>
<i>Allied fighter aircraft</i>
<i>out of commission.</i>

140
00:12:30,216 --> 00:12:34,520
<i>Imperial Japanese troops</i>
<i>have practically surrounded</i>
<i>Henderson Field.</i>

141
00:12:34,553 --> 00:12:38,757
<i>Allied ground forces</i>
<i>have had no supplies</i>
<i>or reinforcements.</i>

142
00:12:38,791 --> 00:12:43,062
<i>In his opinion, Guadalcanal</i>
<i>will be in Japanese hands</i>
<i>within four days.</i>

143
00:12:44,296 --> 00:12:45,798
<i>How sure is he?</i>

144
00:12:47,967 --> 00:12:51,036
<i>Well, here's a plan</i>
<i>for the surrender ceremony.</i>

145
00:13:01,680 --> 00:13:05,751
<i>Yamamoto is delighted</i>
<i>with the plan.</i>
<i>Lauds Kobe for his initiative.</i>

146
00:13:06,485 --> 00:13:08,320
(BOTH SPEAK JAPANESE)

147
00:13:14,093 --> 00:13:16,962
<i>NARRATOR: The paper draws</i>
<i>Yamamoto's attention.</i>

148
00:13:16,996 --> 00:13:20,866
<i>An American flying boat</i>
<i>spotted enroute</i>
<i>to Guadalcanal.</i>

149
00:13:20,900 --> 00:13:26,005
<i>To Kobe it is an item</i>
<i>of no consequence,</i>
<i>but Yamamoto is interested.</i>

150
00:13:26,038 --> 00:13:28,874
<i>Several high-ranking American</i>
<i>officers at Pearl Harbor</i>

151
00:13:28,908 --> 00:13:34,046
<i>have been unaccounted</i>
<i>for the past three days.</i>
<i>They could be anywhere.</i>

152
00:13:34,079 --> 00:13:38,150
<i>The odds against their being</i>
<i>on that flying boat</i>
<i>are incalculable,</i>

153
00:13:38,184 --> 00:13:40,653
 <i>but the old poker player</i>
 <i>has a hunch.</i>

154
00:13:40,686 --> 00:13:43,689
<i>When you get a hunch,</i>
<i>bet a hunch.</i>

155
00:13:43,722 --> 00:13:48,394
<i>He orders 20 Zeros</i>
<i>to intercept the flying boat</i>
<i>on its arrival at Guadalcanal.</i>

156
00:13:49,695 --> 00:13:51,931
Won't be long now.

157
00:13:51,964 --> 00:13:54,867
Andy just sent
an ETA for 0600.

158
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:58,404
That's less than an hour.
We must've picked up
a tail wind.

159
00:13:58,437 --> 00:13:59,538
Yeah.

160
00:14:00,539 --> 00:14:02,208
Sit down,
sit down.

161
00:14:03,042 --> 00:14:05,444
Sleep well,
Admiral?
Fine.

162
00:14:05,477 --> 00:14:08,581
That pill really
did the trick, huh? Yeah.
Slept like a baby.

163
00:14:08,614 --> 00:14:11,550
We've gone through
all the reports
on this area, sir.

164
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:13,018
What do you make
of them?

165
00:14:13,052 --> 00:14:16,689
What can we make of them?
We're losing our shirt.

166
00:14:16,722 --> 00:14:19,758
Granted. Our job is
to find out why.

167
00:14:19,792 --> 00:14:22,595
Primarily, I think it's
a matter of logistics.

168
00:14:22,628 --> 00:14:27,766
Logistics hell, it's morale.
Command. I say they ought to
send in a new pitcher.

169
00:14:36,141 --> 00:14:38,611
Relieve Admiral Ghormley?
Yes, sir.

170
00:14:44,683 --> 00:14:47,987
Until we've acquainted
ourselves with the situation,

171
00:14:49,255 --> 00:14:51,657
I suggest
we reserve our opinions.

172
00:14:53,259 --> 00:14:54,827
FRANK: Yes, sir.

173
00:15:01,533 --> 00:15:05,838
For your information,
the old man thinks the world
of Admiral Ghormley.

174
00:15:06,639 --> 00:15:08,440
They're old friends.

175
00:15:13,979 --> 00:15:15,814
What's our position,
Andy?

176
00:15:15,848 --> 00:15:18,784
We're three minutes
ahead of
flight plan, sir.

177
00:15:20,619 --> 00:15:22,955
How long you been
on this course?

178
00:15:23,455 --> 00:15:25,190
About an hour, sir.

179
00:15:26,825 --> 00:15:29,128
What's the weather
at Guadalcanal?

180
00:15:29,161 --> 00:15:31,930
Forecast is for clear.

181
00:15:31,964 --> 00:15:34,900
Is anything wrong, sir,
with the flight plan?

182
00:15:40,806 --> 00:15:43,008
How's it going, Chief?
Fine, Admiral.

183
00:15:43,042 --> 00:15:45,444
Been receiving Noumea
loud and clear.

184
00:15:45,477 --> 00:15:46,645
Anything new?

185
00:15:46,679 --> 00:15:48,013
No, sir.

186
00:15:48,047 --> 00:15:54,720
Except this
wasn't sent to us,
but I picked it up.

187
00:15:54,753 --> 00:15:59,825
ANDY: Noumea's reporting
unusual Japanese radio traffic
between Truk and Guadalcanal.

188
00:16:07,166 --> 00:16:08,434
Sit down.

189
00:16:11,837 --> 00:16:14,640
I think we'll pass up
Guadalcanal.

190
00:16:14,673 --> 00:16:18,243
Tell Andy to change course
to Noumea, direct.

191
00:16:18,277 --> 00:16:19,778
Aye, aye, sir.

192
00:16:24,383 --> 00:16:29,054
<i>NARRATOR: Admiral Yamamoto</i>
<i>was not the only hunch player</i>
<i>in the South Pacific.</i>

193
00:16:33,692 --> 00:16:35,027
(WHIRRING)

194
00:16:40,132 --> 00:16:43,702
<i>Sixty-five hundred miles</i>
<i>to the east</i>
<i>in Washington, D.C.,</i>

195
00:16:43,736 --> 00:16:47,072
<i>seated at his desk,</i>
<i>a man is talking</i>
<i>on the telephone.</i>

196
00:16:47,106 --> 00:16:50,642
KING: Good, sir. I'm glad
you concur, Mr. President.

197
00:16:52,411 --> 00:16:57,316
Yes. Thank you, sir. Goodbye.

198
00:17:02,321 --> 00:17:05,724
Operator, do you still have
Pearl Harbor on the line?

199
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:09,228
<i>KING: Hello, Chester.</i>
Yes, Ernie?

200
00:17:10,729 --> 00:17:13,632
<i>KING: We just got</i>
<i>the green light</i>
<i>from the White House.</i>

201
00:17:13,665 --> 00:17:17,770
He's in the air right now.
He doesn't have any decoding
equipment on the plane.

202
00:17:47,433 --> 00:17:49,935
Pulaski of
Admiral Ghormley's staff.
Good trip, sir?

203
00:17:50,636 --> 00:17:52,237
Uneventful, I'm glad to say.

204
00:17:52,271 --> 00:17:54,807
You were to
receive this
at once, sir.

205
00:18:10,622 --> 00:18:13,659
<i>PULASKI: You will relieve</i>
<i>Admiral Ghormley</i>
<i>and take command</i>

206
00:18:13,692 --> 00:18:18,464
<i>of the South Pacific area</i>
<i>and South Pacific forces</i>
<i>immediately.</i>

207
00:18:28,307 --> 00:18:30,843
Oh, damn. That's what
I call a smart move.

208
00:18:38,350 --> 00:18:39,651
Where's
Admiral Ghormley?

209
00:18:39,685 --> 00:18:42,788
He's waiting for you
on the
<i>Argonne,</i> sir.

210
00:18:42,821 --> 00:18:44,823
All right, Andy.
Let's go.

211
00:18:53,398 --> 00:18:58,070
<i>NARRATOR: He and Ghormley had</i>
<i>played on the same football</i>
<i>team at the Naval Academy.</i>

212
00:18:58,103 --> 00:19:00,672
<i>They'd been friends</i>
<i>for 40 years,</i>

213
00:19:13,185 --> 00:19:14,620
(SHIP BLOWS HORN)

214
00:19:20,692 --> 00:19:23,095
<i>Vice Admiral</i>
<i>Robert L. Ghormley.</i>

215
00:19:23,128 --> 00:19:26,031
 <i>Born in Portland, Oregon</i>
 <i>in 1883.</i>

216
00:19:26,064 --> 00:19:29,835
<i>At the age of 10 his family</i>
<i>moved to Moscow, Idaho</i>

217
00:19:29,868 --> 00:19:32,337
 <i>where he received</i>
 <i>all his early education.</i>

218
00:19:32,371 --> 00:19:38,510
<i>Phi Beta Kappa, graduated 12th</i>
<i>in his class</i>
<i>at the Naval Academy in 1906.</i>

219
00:19:38,544 --> 00:19:42,214
<i>In Admiral Ghormley's life</i>
<i>there is no room for anything</i>
<i>but Navy.</i>

220
00:20:18,784 --> 00:20:20,452
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

221
00:20:21,653 --> 00:20:23,922
Permission to
come aboard, sir?

222
00:20:48,447 --> 00:20:51,783
Good to see you, Bill.
Good to see you, Ghorm.

223
00:20:51,817 --> 00:20:53,785
You know my orders?
Yeah.

224
00:20:55,487 --> 00:20:59,458
Hottest potato
they ever handed me.
I don't envy you.

225
00:20:59,491 --> 00:21:02,794
I suppose you were
prepared for it?
No. Not a hint of it.

226
00:21:02,828 --> 00:21:05,530
I still can't believe it.
Neither can I.

227
00:21:07,799 --> 00:21:12,437
What made them do it?
I haven't got your brains
nor your ability.

228
00:21:12,471 --> 00:21:13,538
And after what
you've been through...

229
00:21:13,572 --> 00:21:17,442
They'll never know
what we've been through
down here.

230
00:21:17,476 --> 00:21:20,646
Well, maybe they just
wanted you to have a rest.
Lord knows you've earned it.

231
00:21:20,679 --> 00:21:22,214
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

232
00:21:22,247 --> 00:21:23,482
Come in.

233
00:21:26,685 --> 00:21:28,453
Excuse me, sir.

234
00:21:28,487 --> 00:21:31,790
I've finally contacted all
the key commanders about
your conference this evening.

235
00:21:31,823 --> 00:21:35,027
General Vandergrift
is doubtful,
but the others can get away.

236
00:21:35,060 --> 00:21:37,496
What time will
suit the Admiral?

237
00:21:37,529 --> 00:21:39,164
Up to you, Bill.

238
00:21:39,831 --> 00:21:41,667
Whatever you decide.

239
00:21:45,003 --> 00:21:48,006
Admiral Halsey
will advise you later.
Aye, sir.

240
00:21:53,045 --> 00:21:58,483
Ghorm, why is the Navy
taking such a licking
at Guadalcanal?

241
00:21:58,517 --> 00:22:03,021
That's easy. Our people
are worn out with day
and night operations.

242
00:22:03,055 --> 00:22:06,858
Our search planes didn't
see them coming and we
were taken by surprise.

243
00:22:06,892 --> 00:22:09,728
Yamamoto's commanders
are better trained
for night fighting.

244
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:12,698
They employed
their torpedoes better.

245
00:22:12,731 --> 00:22:15,267
But we're learning fast,
I plan to...

246
00:22:21,206 --> 00:22:24,042
Let's get this change of
command over with.

247
00:22:25,777 --> 00:22:28,880
Ask Admiral Halsey's Chief
of Staff and my Chief
of Staff to come in here.

248
00:22:28,914 --> 00:22:30,215
Aye, sir.

249
00:22:33,885 --> 00:22:36,054
I saw George Baker at Pearl.

250
00:22:36,088 --> 00:22:38,690
(CHUCKLES)
How is he?
Oh, fine.

251
00:22:38,724 --> 00:22:41,026
He told me he ran into
Joe Masefield
about a year ago.

252
00:22:41,059 --> 00:22:42,394
Good. Bill,

253
00:22:46,398 --> 00:22:47,899
what did I do wrong?

254
00:22:51,236 --> 00:22:54,639
You didn't do anything wrong.
You just got here first.

255
00:22:56,908 --> 00:23:01,747
And I'm going to get a lot
of the credit for many of
the things that you started.

256
00:23:03,782 --> 00:23:04,983
Thanks.

257
00:23:10,088 --> 00:23:12,324
<i>NARRATOR: Admiral Yamamoto</i>
<i>makes it a point to relax</i>

258
00:23:12,357 --> 00:23:15,260
<i>between the hours of 1:00</i>
<i>and 2:00 each afternoon.</i>

259
00:23:15,293 --> 00:23:19,664
<i>Sometimes he naps,</i>
<i>sometimes he reads,</i>
<i>sometimes he plays chess.</i>

260
00:23:21,433 --> 00:23:26,104
<i>Today it's photography.</i>
<i>The camera is a Leica</i>
<i>with a 2,8 lens.</i>

261
00:23:26,138 --> 00:23:28,540
<i>The subject is</i>
<i>a crimson hibiscus.</i>

262
00:23:29,941 --> 00:23:31,610
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

263
00:23:39,184 --> 00:23:42,254
 <i>NARRATOR: In case you do not</i>
 <i>understand what is being said,</i>

264
00:23:42,287 --> 00:23:47,292
<i>Yamamoto is being advised</i>
<i>that Admiral Ghormley has been</i>
<i>relieved by Admiral Halsey.</i>

265
00:23:48,894 --> 00:23:50,829
<i>Yamamoto and Kobe</i>
<i>share the opinion</i>

266
00:23:50,862 --> 00:23:56,501
<i>that the American situation</i>
<i>is too far gone to be saved</i>
<i>by a change of command.</i>

267
00:23:56,535 --> 00:24:01,940
<i>They figure it will take</i>
<i>Halsey at least 30 days</i>
<i>just to learn the new job,</i>

268
00:24:01,973 --> 00:24:04,309
<i>and by then,</i>
<i>it will be too late.</i>

269
00:24:07,846 --> 00:24:09,714
<i>Wait just a minute.</i>

270
00:24:09,748 --> 00:24:13,785
<i>It was Halsey who led the</i>
<i>spectacular and successful</i>
<i>raids on the Marshalls.</i>

271
00:24:13,819 --> 00:24:16,455
 <i>It was Halsey</i>
 <i>who raided Wake Island.</i>

272
00:24:16,488 --> 00:24:19,457
 <i>It was Halsey</i>
 <i>who raided the Marcus Islands.</i>

273
00:24:19,491 --> 00:24:24,129
<i>It was Halsey who launched the</i>
<i>incredible Doolittle attack</i>
<i>against Tokyo.</i>

274
00:24:24,162 --> 00:24:27,566
<i>The filming of the crimson</i>
<i>hibiscus will have to wait.</i>

275
00:24:33,505 --> 00:24:35,307
We have five days.

276
00:24:35,340 --> 00:24:40,011
Six at the most, before
Yamamoto's next big push.

277
00:24:40,045 --> 00:24:43,315
My immediate handicap
is ignorance of the area.

278
00:24:43,348 --> 00:24:45,984
I've never been
on Guadalcanal.

279
00:24:46,017 --> 00:24:48,854
You know the problem.
You know what needs
to be done.

280
00:24:48,887 --> 00:24:54,426
Do it. I'll back you.
And throw away the book.

281
00:24:54,459 --> 00:24:56,528
The guy who wrote it
was never in this situation.

282
00:24:56,561 --> 00:24:58,330
And one more thing,

283
00:24:58,363 --> 00:25:01,166
forget whether
you're the Army,
Navy, Marine,

284
00:25:01,199 --> 00:25:04,703
Australian,
New Zealand or British.

285
00:25:04,736 --> 00:25:07,372
We'll operate as though
we are all in one uniform,

286
00:25:07,405 --> 00:25:10,175
if I have to stencil
South Pacific Fighting Force

287
00:25:10,208 --> 00:25:11,943
on the seat
of every man's pants.

288
00:25:12,410 --> 00:25:14,679
(ALL LAUGH)

289
00:25:14,713 --> 00:25:19,084
Those of you wearing neckties
may begin by taking them off

290
00:25:19,117 --> 00:25:21,353
because if you're as busy
as you're going to be,

291
00:25:21,386 --> 00:25:24,389
or as you should be,
you won't have time
to put them on.

292
00:25:26,758 --> 00:25:29,160
My cabin door
will always be open.

293
00:25:31,730 --> 00:25:33,064
Good luck.

294
00:25:35,934 --> 00:25:38,069
Captain Black,

295
00:25:38,103 --> 00:25:42,007
will you see me
in my cabin in about
five minutes?

296
00:25:53,752 --> 00:25:56,855
Sit down, Captain.
I'll be with you in a minute.

297
00:26:05,263 --> 00:26:06,998
<i>NARRATOR: Admiral Ghormley's</i>
<i>Chief of Staff,</i>

298
00:26:07,032 --> 00:26:10,902
<i>Captain Harry Black,</i>
<i>class of 1919 at Annapolis.</i>

299
00:26:10,936 --> 00:26:15,573
<i>He knows the book.</i>
<i>He thinks by the book.</i>
<i>And he operates by the book.</i>

300
00:26:15,607 --> 00:26:17,575
<i>A former commanding officer</i>
<i>once commented that</i>

301
00:26:17,609 --> 00:26:19,644
 <i>he was too smart</i>
 <i>for his own good.</i>

302
00:26:19,678 --> 00:26:21,546
<i>He would be the first</i>
<i>to deny this.</i>

303
00:26:28,787 --> 00:26:31,122
What's the beef,
Mr. Black?

304
00:26:31,156 --> 00:26:32,824
I think Admiral Ghormley
got a bad deal.

305
00:26:32,857 --> 00:26:34,592
For which you blame me.
I didn't say that, Admiral.

306
00:26:34,626 --> 00:26:36,594
You didn't have to.

307
00:26:36,628 --> 00:26:38,463
Now, if it's any
consolation,

308
00:26:38,496 --> 00:26:42,000
I think Admiral Ghormley
did as good a job,
if not better,

309
00:26:42,033 --> 00:26:44,936
than anybody else
could've done under
existing conditions.

310
00:26:44,970 --> 00:26:48,206
It takes quite some time
to learn about conditions
down here, sir.

311
00:26:51,242 --> 00:26:53,144
Yes, I'm sure it does.

312
00:26:54,813 --> 00:26:56,414
And you're going to
educate me.

313
00:26:58,316 --> 00:27:01,052
You want me to stay on?
Of course.

314
00:27:01,086 --> 00:27:03,655
May I ask why, sir?

315
00:27:03,688 --> 00:27:07,158
I'd be a fool not to take
advantage of your experience.

316
00:27:11,863 --> 00:27:14,132
How do I get a quick
and accurate picture

317
00:27:14,165 --> 00:27:15,500
of our situation
on Guadalcanal?

318
00:27:17,002 --> 00:27:18,336
Talk to the key commanders.

319
00:27:18,370 --> 00:27:21,673
Vandergrift, Geiger, Patch,
Carlson, Harmon, Turner.

320
00:27:23,108 --> 00:27:24,709
How soon can
you get them here?

321
00:27:24,743 --> 00:27:26,177
20:00, sir.

322
00:27:27,012 --> 00:27:28,847
Do it.
Aye, aye, sir.

323
00:27:48,199 --> 00:27:49,868
(WOMAN LAUGHING)

324
00:27:58,243 --> 00:27:59,811
(BOTH LAUGHING)

325
00:28:00,945 --> 00:28:03,515
Good evening, sir.

326
00:28:03,548 --> 00:28:07,352
Miss Young, sir, came aboard
on behalf of the Red Cross
Entertainment Committee.

327
00:28:07,385 --> 00:28:12,357
She's making a survey
to see what the men
would enjoy the most.

328
00:28:12,390 --> 00:28:15,560
I'm sure Commander Lowe
will have some
excellent suggestions.

329
00:28:15,593 --> 00:28:16,694
Would you believe it,
sir?

330
00:28:16,728 --> 00:28:19,097
Miss Young and I
grew up in the same town,

331
00:28:19,130 --> 00:28:22,667
but never laid eyes
on each other until
five minutes ago.

332
00:28:25,003 --> 00:28:26,738
About five minutes.

333
00:28:29,941 --> 00:28:31,743
It is a small world.

334
00:28:35,447 --> 00:28:37,115
Carry on.
Yes, sir.

335
00:29:05,343 --> 00:29:08,113
Make yourselves
comfortable.
Sit anywhere.

336
00:29:08,680 --> 00:29:10,181
(BELL RINGING)

337
00:29:13,318 --> 00:29:14,986
Any of you gentlemen
need medication?

338
00:29:15,019 --> 00:29:16,654
I could stand a taste.

339
00:29:16,688 --> 00:29:18,723
I'll have some
coffee, Doc.

340
00:29:19,624 --> 00:29:21,025
Thank you.

341
00:29:21,059 --> 00:29:22,794
 <i>NARRATOR: Major General</i>
 <i>Millard F. Harmon,</i>

342
00:29:22,827 --> 00:29:25,463
<i>Commander of</i>
<i>the Army Air Force</i>
<i>in the South Pacific.</i>

343
00:29:25,497 --> 00:29:29,033
<i>Won the Croix de Guerre</i>
<i>with Bronze Star</i>
<i>in World War I.</i>

344
00:29:29,067 --> 00:29:30,835
<i>At his order</i>
 Flying Fortresses

345
00:29:30,869 --> 00:29:34,339
<i>now drop their bombs</i>
<i>from altitudes</i>
<i>as low as 200 feet.</i>

346
00:29:35,507 --> 00:29:37,842
HALSEY: How about you,
Colonel?
CARLSON: Sir?

347
00:29:37,876 --> 00:29:40,879
The good doctor
has authorized
a combat ration.

348
00:29:40,912 --> 00:29:42,614
Not unless you're
having something, sir.

349
00:29:42,647 --> 00:29:44,549
I'm not eligible
aboard ship.

350
00:29:44,582 --> 00:29:47,118
Maybe when I visit
your raiders
on Guadalcanal.

351
00:29:47,152 --> 00:29:48,987
You'll be eligible,
sir.

352
00:29:49,020 --> 00:29:52,557
<i>NARRATOR: Colonel</i>
<i>Evans Carlson,</i>
<i>enlisted in the Army at 16.</i>

353
00:29:52,590 --> 00:29:54,659
<i>Served in the Philippines,</i>
<i>Hawaiian Islands,</i>

354
00:29:54,692 --> 00:29:57,829
<i>at the Mexican border</i>
<i>and in World War I.</i>

355
00:29:57,862 --> 00:30:03,334
<i>Created and commands</i>
<i>the American Guerilla Unit</i>
<i>known as Carlson's Raiders.</i>

356
00:30:03,368 --> 00:30:06,204
General Vandergrift
and General Geiger,
sir.

357
00:30:08,039 --> 00:30:09,474
Hello, sir.

358
00:30:09,507 --> 00:30:11,176
Roy.
Admiral.

359
00:30:11,209 --> 00:30:13,411
You all know
General Vandergrift
and General Geiger.

360
00:30:13,444 --> 00:30:15,513
Gentlemen.
How are you, sir?

361
00:30:15,547 --> 00:30:16,648
Sorry we're late,
sir.

362
00:30:16,681 --> 00:30:19,017
We ran into
a little excitement
around takeoff time.

363
00:30:19,050 --> 00:30:21,286
Yeah. Washing
Machine Charlie.

364
00:30:22,554 --> 00:30:23,955
Have a seat.

365
00:30:26,891 --> 00:30:28,693
Excuse me, gentlemen.

366
00:30:30,895 --> 00:30:33,865
Archie, how bad is it?

367
00:30:35,867 --> 00:30:37,902
Whatever they've told you,
it's worse.

368
00:30:37,936 --> 00:30:43,341
Mud, malaria, mosquitoes,
dengue fever, dysentery...

369
00:30:43,374 --> 00:30:46,177
<i>NARRATOR: Major General</i>
<i>Alexander Archer Vandergrift,</i>

370
00:30:46,211 --> 00:30:49,180
<i>Commander of</i>
<i>all Marines on Guadalcanal.</i>

371
00:30:49,214 --> 00:30:51,883
<i>Nickname, "Sunny Jim."</i>

372
00:30:51,916 --> 00:30:55,853
<i>His favorite General,</i>
<i>Stonewall Jackson.</i>

373
00:30:55,887 --> 00:30:59,557
We're living on captured rice,
driving our trucks
on captured gas.

374
00:30:59,591 --> 00:31:03,761
What are we short of?
Kelly Turner can tell you.

375
00:31:03,795 --> 00:31:08,399
Ammunition, food, medicine,
tools, spare parts, pilots,

376
00:31:08,433 --> 00:31:12,403
aircraft, ground troops...
Everything except Japs.

377
00:31:12,437 --> 00:31:14,138
It's been that way
ever since we landed.

378
00:31:14,172 --> 00:31:16,608
If you think the Navy's
been letting you down, Archie,

379
00:31:16,641 --> 00:31:20,245
let's you and me trade places
for about 24 hours.

380
00:31:20,278 --> 00:31:21,913
Maybe then
you'll get some idea...

381
00:31:21,946 --> 00:31:24,115
<i>NARRATOR: Rear Admiral</i>
<i>Kelly Turner.</i>

382
00:31:24,148 --> 00:31:27,385
<i>His job, organize the</i>
<i>transports and supply ships.</i>

383
00:31:27,418 --> 00:31:29,721
<i>His motto,</i>
<i>"If you don't have losses,</i>

384
00:31:29,754 --> 00:31:32,790
<i>"you aren't doing enough."</i>
<i>His hobby, gardening.</i>

385
00:31:33,825 --> 00:31:35,994
How the hell I'm gonna give
more naval support

386
00:31:36,027 --> 00:31:38,930
when I don't have the ships,
cargo or combat?

387
00:31:38,963 --> 00:31:42,100
I just don't have the ships.

388
00:31:42,133 --> 00:31:44,902
So we let the Tokyo Express
keep cruising down the Slot

389
00:31:44,936 --> 00:31:47,572
every night pouring shells
onto Henderson Field.

390
00:31:47,605 --> 00:31:51,142
We're down to just one carrier
in the whole South Pacific,

391
00:31:51,175 --> 00:31:54,112
until the
<i>Enterprise</i>
gets back from Pearl.

392
00:31:54,145 --> 00:31:55,246
Roy?

393
00:31:55,280 --> 00:31:57,415
 <i>NARRATOR: Major General</i>
 <i>Roy G. Geiger,</i>

394
00:31:57,448 --> 00:32:00,785
<i>Commander of all aviation</i>
<i>units on Guadalcanal.</i>

395
00:32:00,818 --> 00:32:04,522
<i>He's had seven and a half</i>
<i>hours sleep</i>
<i>in the last four days.</i>

396
00:32:05,523 --> 00:32:08,660
Maintenance in that mud
is a nightmare.

397
00:32:08,693 --> 00:32:11,696
We're lucky to get up
six aircraft against 30.

398
00:32:12,797 --> 00:32:15,133
Admiral, this morning
I had to kick,

399
00:32:15,166 --> 00:32:17,201
literally kick
a couple of pilots awake

400
00:32:17,235 --> 00:32:19,537
to drive them back
into their cockpits.

401
00:32:19,570 --> 00:32:21,673
They were that beat.

402
00:32:21,706 --> 00:32:25,376
Admiral, unless
the Navy shows
the flag up there soon,

403
00:32:25,410 --> 00:32:27,945
I can't answer
for the outcome.

404
00:32:27,979 --> 00:32:31,015
TURNER: How can we protect
transports in those
restricted waters?

405
00:32:31,049 --> 00:32:33,318
I'd have to commit
what's left of my task force

406
00:32:33,351 --> 00:32:35,019
and risk losing
the whole works.

407
00:32:35,053 --> 00:32:37,722
Which is exactly the risk
I'm running right now.

408
00:32:37,755 --> 00:32:39,290
And me.

409
00:32:39,324 --> 00:32:42,860
Sir, the fact of the matter
is, we all share
General Vandergrift's feeling.

410
00:32:42,894 --> 00:32:45,530
Everybody's asking,
"Where's the Navy?"

411
00:32:49,100 --> 00:32:51,169
Anyone else care to speak?

412
00:32:54,572 --> 00:32:56,207
You painted
a black picture, gentlemen.

413
00:32:58,076 --> 00:32:59,944
It's black, all right,

414
00:33:02,180 --> 00:33:04,782
but it can get
a hell of a lot blacker.

415
00:33:06,284 --> 00:33:08,853
Less than a year ago we were
clobbered at Pearl Harbor

416
00:33:10,521 --> 00:33:12,724
and they've been
pushing us back ever since.

417
00:33:12,757 --> 00:33:16,761
Now, Guadalcanal is
the keystone of our defense.

418
00:33:18,429 --> 00:33:20,698
If we lose Guadalcanal,

419
00:33:20,732 --> 00:33:25,770
there'll be nothing
to stop them going all
the way down to Australia.

420
00:33:25,803 --> 00:33:28,539
They'll cut
our lines of communication,

421
00:33:28,573 --> 00:33:30,875
they'll cut
our lines of supply,

422
00:33:32,076 --> 00:33:36,981
the war could be
prolonged for years. Or worse.

423
00:33:40,218 --> 00:33:42,420
Guadalcanal is our
last chance.

424
00:33:45,390 --> 00:33:48,059
I promise you
everything I've got.

425
00:33:48,092 --> 00:33:49,327
The Navy will be there.

426
00:33:50,795 --> 00:33:53,531
I'll get you more
air support

427
00:33:53,564 --> 00:33:55,533
and I'll step up
your supplies.

428
00:33:55,566 --> 00:33:58,603
But, Admiral, even if I could
scrape up enough supply ships,

429
00:33:58,636 --> 00:34:02,573
every time there's an
air alert they have to
quit unloading and pull out.

430
00:34:02,607 --> 00:34:04,075
Then we'll step up
the unloading.

431
00:34:06,577 --> 00:34:07,578
Yes, sir.

432
00:34:08,513 --> 00:34:13,584
All right.
Let's get down to cases.

433
00:34:13,618 --> 00:34:15,219
OFFICER1: Goodnight, Colonel.
OFFICER 2: Goodnight, sir.

434
00:34:15,253 --> 00:34:17,488
Goodnight, Admiral.
Thank you very much.

435
00:34:17,522 --> 00:34:20,391
Admiral,
good luck.
Goodnight, Admiral.

436
00:34:20,425 --> 00:34:22,093
Come and visit us.

437
00:34:25,296 --> 00:34:29,066
<i>OFFICER ON PA: Now hear this.</i>
<i>Call away number one,</i>
<i>motor whaleboat.</i>

438
00:34:29,100 --> 00:34:32,103
Well, you sure
made them feel better.

439
00:34:34,806 --> 00:34:39,277
Admiral, where you gonna get
all that stuff you promised?

440
00:34:45,650 --> 00:34:47,118
I don't know.

441
00:34:48,553 --> 00:34:50,121
(BELL RINGING)

442
00:34:55,526 --> 00:34:59,363
Now, where can
I lay my hands
on some ground troops

443
00:34:59,397 --> 00:35:00,998
and get them
to Guadalcanal?

444
00:35:01,032 --> 00:35:03,601
I'm afraid the bottom
of the barrel has already
been scraped bare, sir,

445
00:35:03,634 --> 00:35:05,470
by Admiral Ghormley.

446
00:35:06,170 --> 00:35:07,638
Are you sure?

447
00:35:09,540 --> 00:35:12,543
What about this proposed
airstrip at in the Dai,

448
00:35:12,577 --> 00:35:15,379
and the Army ground troops
we're sending in to build it?

449
00:35:15,413 --> 00:35:17,648
They're committed.
They're on their way.

450
00:35:17,682 --> 00:35:20,451
Why can't we divert them
to the island, tonight?

451
00:35:20,485 --> 00:35:22,653
But, Admiral,
there's a specific
directive.

452
00:35:22,687 --> 00:35:25,990
But we are faced
with one hell
of an emergency.

453
00:35:26,023 --> 00:35:27,492
The airstrip
isn't that essential.

454
00:35:27,525 --> 00:35:30,728
It's 205 miles
closer to Henderson
than any we've got, sir.

455
00:35:30,761 --> 00:35:34,131
So we increase
our air search area
205 miles.

456
00:35:34,165 --> 00:35:37,802
But that does not save
25,000 men on Guadalcanal.

457
00:35:37,835 --> 00:35:40,138
Admiral, by the time
we went through channels
to try to change...

458
00:35:40,171 --> 00:35:42,340
There won't be time
for channels.

459
00:35:42,373 --> 00:35:44,242
I tell you,
unless we move now,

460
00:35:44,275 --> 00:35:46,711
there won't be any need
for that airstrip.

461
00:35:46,744 --> 00:35:49,213
And, Harry, there's only
one thing to do,

462
00:35:49,247 --> 00:35:51,983
intercept those ground troops
and send them where
they'll do the most good.

463
00:35:52,016 --> 00:35:55,019
And ignore
the directive?
We can argue with them later.

464
00:35:55,052 --> 00:35:56,754
But, Admiral,
we can't do that.

465
00:35:56,787 --> 00:36:01,559
I think we'd be entirely wrong
to take such a decision
into our own hands.

466
00:36:01,592 --> 00:36:05,763
Is that your best judgment?
It's my frank opinion, sir.

467
00:36:05,796 --> 00:36:07,498
Are you prepared
for the consequences?

468
00:36:07,532 --> 00:36:08,666
I am, sir.

469
00:36:08,699 --> 00:36:12,837
I mean the consequences
of losing Guadalcanal?

470
00:36:12,870 --> 00:36:15,940
Or are you concerned with
repercussions from topside?

471
00:36:15,973 --> 00:36:18,543
It isn't just a matter of
repercussions, sir,

472
00:36:18,576 --> 00:36:21,012
I think it would be fairer
to say, that I believe
that these things

473
00:36:21,045 --> 00:36:22,613
have to be
properly coordinated.

474
00:36:30,454 --> 00:36:34,425
I'm afraid you'll have to
leave that one to me, Harry.

475
00:36:34,458 --> 00:36:38,896
Issue the necessary orders,
and advise Harmon,
Patch and Vandergrift.

476
00:36:40,097 --> 00:36:41,599
Aye, aye, sir.

477
00:36:44,502 --> 00:36:46,470
Harry?
Sir.

478
00:36:48,239 --> 00:36:50,474
Ask Pulaski
to come in, please.

479
00:36:52,910 --> 00:36:54,145
Yes, sir.

480
00:36:55,112 --> 00:36:58,049
MALE VOICE: You know,
I missed that shot.

481
00:36:58,082 --> 00:37:00,218
Lieutenant Pulaski,
the Admiral wants
to see you.

482
00:37:00,251 --> 00:37:01,586
Thank you.

483
00:37:04,488 --> 00:37:05,590
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

484
00:37:05,623 --> 00:37:06,857
Come in.

485
00:37:10,294 --> 00:37:11,596
Have a seat, Mike.

486
00:37:11,629 --> 00:37:14,332
Quite a bunch out there
still waiting to see you,
sir.

487
00:37:14,365 --> 00:37:15,600
I know.

488
00:37:17,101 --> 00:37:18,769
The pieces beginning to
fit together?

489
00:37:18,803 --> 00:37:20,805
Little by little.

490
00:37:20,838 --> 00:37:24,475
Mike, just how good
is our Intelligence?

491
00:37:24,508 --> 00:37:28,646
Well, the Polynesians resent
the Japs, so they help us.

492
00:37:28,679 --> 00:37:30,581
Missionaries
and Australian coast-watchers

493
00:37:30,615 --> 00:37:32,817
in hiding
along the Solomon's chain

494
00:37:32,850 --> 00:37:37,288
tip us to Jap ships coming
down the slot and air raids.

495
00:37:37,321 --> 00:37:40,258
I've got two men with radios,
here on Rendova.

496
00:37:40,291 --> 00:37:43,261
One in the Shortland's,
and several, here,
in the Russell's.

497
00:37:43,294 --> 00:37:44,962
That's right under
the Japs' noses.

498
00:37:44,996 --> 00:37:47,531
How do they evade
capture?
Some don't.

499
00:37:50,301 --> 00:37:51,702
I see.

500
00:37:51,736 --> 00:37:54,772
Mike, they tell me you're
an expert on the Orient.

501
00:37:54,805 --> 00:37:58,109
Not an expert.
Spent some
years in Japan.

502
00:37:58,142 --> 00:38:01,345
Speak the language,
know most of their
leaders personally.

503
00:38:01,379 --> 00:38:03,781
Tojo, Nomura,
Admiral Yamamoto...

504
00:38:03,814 --> 00:38:05,516
What can you tell me
about Yamamoto?

505
00:38:05,549 --> 00:38:09,453
He's the best they've got.
A fine tactician,
a brilliant strategist,

506
00:38:09,487 --> 00:38:11,989
he commands the
fanatical loyalty of his men.

507
00:38:12,023 --> 00:38:14,625
I understand that
when his fliers
are downed in the water,

508
00:38:14,659 --> 00:38:15,893
they don't even
expect to be picked up.

509
00:38:15,926 --> 00:38:17,161
That's right, sir.

510
00:38:17,194 --> 00:38:20,398
They know he won't
spare planes for rescue.

511
00:38:20,431 --> 00:38:22,800
Nice, very nice.

512
00:38:22,833 --> 00:38:24,301
If you'd like
a personal note, sir,

513
00:38:24,335 --> 00:38:26,470
I can tell you
he's quite a poker player.

514
00:38:26,504 --> 00:38:28,372
You've played with him?
Many times.

515
00:38:28,406 --> 00:38:29,974
When he was naval attache
in Washington.

516
00:38:30,007 --> 00:38:32,176
And he was rough?
Very.

517
00:38:32,209 --> 00:38:34,979
Consistently overplayed
his hand and got away with it.

518
00:38:35,012 --> 00:38:38,349
I hear that he's hot
for naval aviation
and carriers.

519
00:38:38,382 --> 00:38:39,984
That's right, sir.

520
00:38:40,017 --> 00:38:42,887
I guess you know
the part he
played at Pearl?

521
00:38:45,022 --> 00:38:48,225
Just that he was there.
He was there all right.

522
00:38:48,259 --> 00:38:49,827
We recently learned that
it was Yamamoto

523
00:38:49,860 --> 00:38:53,364
who planned and directed
the attack on Pearl Harbor.

524
00:38:53,397 --> 00:38:56,934
Actually Yamamoto
was against war
with the United States.

525
00:38:56,967 --> 00:39:00,071
He predicted that in the end
Japan would lose.

526
00:39:00,104 --> 00:39:02,173
However once the higher-ups
overruled him,

527
00:39:02,206 --> 00:39:04,909
he threw himself
wholeheartedly
into the effort.

528
00:39:04,942 --> 00:39:07,278
Pearl Harbor was
his first assignment.

529
00:39:07,311 --> 00:39:09,580
And it could've been
my last assignment.

530
00:39:09,613 --> 00:39:12,016
If it hadn't been
for engine trouble at sea,

531
00:39:12,049 --> 00:39:16,354
I'd of been caught in
the harbor with the rest
of those poor devils.

532
00:39:16,387 --> 00:39:18,089
Well, thanks, Mike.

533
00:39:18,122 --> 00:39:21,025
It'll be your job from
now on to read
Yamamoto's mind for me.

534
00:39:21,058 --> 00:39:23,427
I'll do my best, sir.
I'm sure you will.

535
00:39:25,229 --> 00:39:28,399
Are your whizz kids
making any headway
with the Japanese code?

536
00:39:28,432 --> 00:39:30,067
Some.

537
00:39:30,101 --> 00:39:31,569
Light a fire under them,
will you?

538
00:39:31,602 --> 00:39:33,637
Yes, sir.
Goodnight, sir.
Goodnight.

539
00:39:33,671 --> 00:39:35,306
And send Andy in, please.
Yes, sir.

540
00:39:44,582 --> 00:39:46,217
You wanted to see me,
sir?

541
00:39:46,250 --> 00:39:48,085
Who else is waiting
out there?
Well, now, let me see.

542
00:39:48,119 --> 00:39:50,388
There's that freighter
captain you sent for.

543
00:39:50,421 --> 00:39:52,089
Three newspaper
correspondents,

544
00:39:52,123 --> 00:39:54,425
a psychological
warfare officer...

545
00:39:54,458 --> 00:39:55,993
(YAWNS)

546
00:39:56,026 --> 00:39:58,829
A psychological
warfare officer
just in from the States.

547
00:39:58,863 --> 00:40:01,732
Am I keeping you up?
No, sir.

548
00:40:01,766 --> 00:40:03,567
Who else is there?
Doc Key for one.

549
00:40:03,601 --> 00:40:06,303
He says if you don't
see him next, he's gonna
bust in here anyway.

550
00:40:06,337 --> 00:40:08,005
Call him.
Yes, sir.

551
00:40:08,939 --> 00:40:10,508
Doc, come on in.

552
00:40:13,477 --> 00:40:14,745
Good evening, Doc.

553
00:40:14,779 --> 00:40:17,181
Good morning might be
closer to it, sir.

554
00:40:17,214 --> 00:40:19,483
Does the Admiral
realize he's been
cooped up in this office

555
00:40:19,517 --> 00:40:23,254
seeing person after
person for 16
consecutive hours?

556
00:40:23,287 --> 00:40:24,588
Is that a record?

557
00:40:24,622 --> 00:40:26,323
No, sir,
it isn't a record,

558
00:40:26,357 --> 00:40:28,626
if you'll pardon
my saying so,
it isn't very smart.

559
00:40:28,659 --> 00:40:31,762
As your chief flight
surgeon, I must insist
that you get more rest.

560
00:40:31,796 --> 00:40:35,266
They tell me there are
men on Guadalcanal
who haven't slept in days.

561
00:40:35,299 --> 00:40:37,268
Yes, sir. But they're
not 60 years old,

562
00:40:37,301 --> 00:40:40,137
and they're not fresh
out of a hospital.

563
00:40:40,171 --> 00:40:42,439
Just give me
one more hour.
No, sir.

564
00:40:42,473 --> 00:40:45,342
As long as I'm here,
there's something else
I might as well attend to.

565
00:40:45,376 --> 00:40:46,644
What's that for?
What're you gonna do?

566
00:40:46,677 --> 00:40:49,380
Your shots, sir.
What do I need
those for?

567
00:40:49,413 --> 00:40:52,817
There's no telling
what you'll run
into on Guadalcanal.

568
00:40:52,850 --> 00:40:55,719
How did you know
I was going up there?

569
00:40:55,753 --> 00:40:58,222
I have friends
in high places.

570
00:40:58,255 --> 00:41:00,224
You tell him?
No, sir.

571
00:41:00,257 --> 00:41:01,859
You know me
better than that.

572
00:41:01,892 --> 00:41:03,227
All right, if you'll just
roll up your sleeve, sir.

573
00:41:03,260 --> 00:41:04,995
Now, wait a minute.

574
00:41:06,263 --> 00:41:09,400
You put that ice pick away
and we'll make a deal.

575
00:41:09,433 --> 00:41:11,869
We're not leaving
until tomorrow afternoon,

576
00:41:11,902 --> 00:41:14,405
you can give me
the shots just
before lunch.

577
00:41:14,438 --> 00:41:16,874
Oh, no.
I won't see
anybody else tonight.

578
00:41:16,907 --> 00:41:20,344
I'll have Andy
clear off the office
and I'll go right to bed.

579
00:41:21,245 --> 00:41:23,481
All right, sir.
It's a deal.

580
00:41:23,514 --> 00:41:26,550
Andy, will you explain the
situation to the people
outside and turn in.

581
00:41:26,584 --> 00:41:28,352
Yes, sir.
Goodnight, Admiral.

582
00:41:28,385 --> 00:41:29,720
Goodnight.

583
00:41:31,922 --> 00:41:35,860
I thought we were taking off
to Guadalcanal at dawn.

584
00:41:35,893 --> 00:41:38,362
We are.
Well, you just told Doc...

585
00:41:39,864 --> 00:41:43,400
Oh, now, sir,
that's real sneaky.

586
00:41:45,236 --> 00:41:46,737
Goodnight, Andy.

587
00:41:46,770 --> 00:41:49,740
All this fuss over a couple
of little bitty old shots.

588
00:41:51,609 --> 00:41:53,210
Goodnight, Andy.

589
00:41:56,480 --> 00:41:58,048
Goodnight, sir.

590
00:42:02,620 --> 00:42:05,923
ANDY: The Admiral
isn't seeing
anybody else tonight.

591
00:42:27,678 --> 00:42:28,879
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

592
00:42:28,913 --> 00:42:30,481
Come in.

593
00:42:30,514 --> 00:42:32,249
HARRY: Captain Black, sir.

594
00:42:37,688 --> 00:42:39,056
What is it, Harry?

595
00:42:39,089 --> 00:42:41,325
About the airstrip
matter, sir.

596
00:42:45,963 --> 00:42:47,064
What about it?

597
00:42:47,097 --> 00:42:48,232
Well, in view of
the position I took,

598
00:42:48,265 --> 00:42:50,901
if a change in my assignment
would be for the best I...

599
00:42:50,935 --> 00:42:52,569
Because you
bucked me on it?

600
00:42:52,603 --> 00:42:55,005
Oh, that's part
of your job.

601
00:42:55,039 --> 00:42:57,675
If we both thought
exactly alike,
I wouldn't need you.

602
00:42:57,708 --> 00:43:00,644
Thank you, sir.
The orders have gone out,
sir.

603
00:43:01,712 --> 00:43:03,514
Now we both better
jump to one side.

604
00:43:03,547 --> 00:43:04,949
I think so, sir.

605
00:43:58,335 --> 00:44:00,471
Welcome to
Guadalcanal, sir.
Thanks.

606
00:44:00,504 --> 00:44:03,907
Captain Bailey.
You remember Andy Lowe?

607
00:44:04,842 --> 00:44:06,076
How do you do?
Anyone else with you?

608
00:44:06,110 --> 00:44:07,711
No. I left them all
on the
<i>Argonne.</i>

609
00:44:07,745 --> 00:44:09,079
I brought you
four sacks of mail

610
00:44:09,113 --> 00:44:12,516
and nine drums of
aviation gasoline instead.

611
00:44:12,549 --> 00:44:16,186
No reflection on your staff,
Admiral, but you couldn't
have made a better switch.

612
00:44:16,220 --> 00:44:20,157
Sergeant, a load
of gas drums
for you and mail.

613
00:44:20,190 --> 00:44:23,227
Yes, sir.
Okay, you guys,
you heard the man.

614
00:44:23,260 --> 00:44:25,529
Well, Admiral,
where can we
take you first?

615
00:44:25,562 --> 00:44:27,998
I don't want to
tie you up.
Just give me a jeep

616
00:44:28,032 --> 00:44:29,366
and a driver
who knows
his way around.

617
00:44:29,400 --> 00:44:31,568
I'll be glad to
go with you.
No thanks.

618
00:44:31,602 --> 00:44:33,837
I prefer to have
a look around
on my own,

619
00:44:33,871 --> 00:44:36,173
while Captain Bailey
gets together with
you and your G-3.

620
00:44:36,206 --> 00:44:38,208
All right, sir.
Lieutenant Ludlum.

621
00:44:38,242 --> 00:44:39,843
Take the Admiral
anyplace he wants to go.

622
00:44:39,877 --> 00:44:41,111
Yes, sir.

623
00:44:44,481 --> 00:44:46,550
<i>NARRATOR: First Lieutenant</i>
<i>Harrison Ludlum.</i>

624
00:44:46,583 --> 00:44:52,556
<i>Age 28. Occupation, printer.</i>
<i>Married, two children.</i>

625
00:44:52,589 --> 00:44:56,126
<i>Thirty-six hours from now</i>
<i>a sniper's bullet</i>
<i>will make him a paraplegic.</i>

626
00:45:11,075 --> 00:45:13,644
That's the Padre,
sir.
Padre?

627
00:45:13,677 --> 00:45:16,380
Father Gehring,
Navy chaplain.
Could we give him a lift?

628
00:45:16,413 --> 00:45:17,915
Of course.

629
00:45:17,948 --> 00:45:19,083
Hey, Padre.

630
00:45:24,955 --> 00:45:28,225
Welcome aboard,
Padre.
PADRE: Thank you, Admiral.

631
00:45:28,258 --> 00:45:29,727
This is Andy Lowe.

632
00:45:29,760 --> 00:45:31,962
Pleased to
meet you.
How do you do?

633
00:45:31,995 --> 00:45:37,067
<i>NARRATOR: Fred Gehring,</i>
<i>naval chaplain,</i>
<i>a Vincentian father.</i>

634
00:45:37,101 --> 00:45:41,939
<i>Served in China 1933 to 1940.</i>
<i>Holds the Legion of Merit.</i>

635
00:45:41,972 --> 00:45:44,374
<i>Speaks Chinese,</i>
<i>plays the fiddle.</i>

636
00:45:45,209 --> 00:45:47,177
How far up are you going?

637
00:45:47,211 --> 00:45:50,781
Maybe a mile, maybe less.
Depends on how things are.

638
00:45:51,882 --> 00:45:53,784
How are things, Father?

639
00:45:55,819 --> 00:45:57,354
Lousy, Admiral.

640
00:46:12,136 --> 00:46:13,904
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

641
00:46:18,642 --> 00:46:21,945
<i>NARRATOR: Lieutenant</i>
<i>Tadashi Nasu.</i>

642
00:46:21,979 --> 00:46:25,816
<i>Taught Chemistry</i>
<i>at the University of Tokyo.</i>
<i>Married, three children.</i>

643
00:46:25,849 --> 00:46:28,051
<i>At 1:00 this morning</i>
<i>he led 50 men</i>

644
00:46:28,085 --> 00:46:30,954
 <i>in an assault against</i>
 <i>a Marine machine-gun position.</i>

645
00:46:30,988 --> 00:46:34,158
 <i>He came closest to</i>
 <i>reaching the objective.</i>

646
00:46:34,191 --> 00:46:36,460
<i>The others</i>
<i>never made it to the creek.</i>

647
00:46:36,493 --> 00:46:38,695
ERIC: That's the
Tenaru River.

648
00:46:40,063 --> 00:46:43,667
We're here,
they're there.

649
00:46:46,670 --> 00:46:48,906
Got it?
Got it.

650
00:46:48,939 --> 00:46:52,743
Okay. So all night long
we're calling
back and forth,

651
00:46:52,776 --> 00:46:55,579
"Tojo's for the birds.
Babe Ruth stinks."

652
00:46:55,612 --> 00:46:57,981
 <i>NARRATOR: Private First Class,</i>
 <i>Eric Lauder.</i>

653
00:46:58,015 --> 00:46:59,917
<i>He mans the 50-caliber</i>
<i>machine gun</i>

654
00:46:59,950 --> 00:47:02,085
<i>that was assaulted</i>
<i>early this morning.</i>

655
00:47:02,119 --> 00:47:04,421
<i>In 15 minutes</i>
<i>he killed 38 men.</i>

656
00:47:05,189 --> 00:47:07,090
<i>He is 19 years of age.</i>

657
00:47:08,025 --> 00:47:10,194
I thought they'd
never stop coming.

658
00:47:11,461 --> 00:47:13,730
Well, supposing
they'd come
around your flank

659
00:47:13,764 --> 00:47:15,365
instead of coming
at you head on?

660
00:47:16,700 --> 00:47:20,237
We wouldn't be here,
Admiral.
You know what I mean?

661
00:47:20,270 --> 00:47:21,838
I know what you mean.

662
00:47:21,872 --> 00:47:24,942
Okay, you guys,
let's go.
Come on, let's go.

663
00:47:27,945 --> 00:47:32,382
<i>NARRATOR: Three men</i>
<i>in that squad will survive</i>
<i>the battle for Guadalcanal.</i>

664
00:47:34,551 --> 00:47:35,953
(EXPLOSIONS THUNDERING)

665
00:47:39,489 --> 00:47:43,293
 <i>Private First Class</i>
 <i>Eric Lauder isn't one of them.</i>

666
00:48:16,994 --> 00:48:18,662
Admiral Halsey,
this is Doc White.

667
00:48:18,695 --> 00:48:20,931
How do you do, Admiral?
I'm pleased to meet you,
Dr. White.

668
00:48:20,964 --> 00:48:22,266
You get on with your work.
Don't let me stop you.

669
00:48:22,299 --> 00:48:23,800
Okay, Admiral.

670
00:48:25,035 --> 00:48:26,837
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

671
00:48:58,635 --> 00:49:00,837
Could you have dinner
with us at Headquarters
tonight, Father?

672
00:49:00,871 --> 00:49:02,272
Well, thank you,
Admiral.

673
00:49:02,306 --> 00:49:04,975
But I've already
promised the
boys of Company F

674
00:49:05,008 --> 00:49:06,910
I'd have chow
with them.

675
00:49:08,312 --> 00:49:11,081
Goodbye, sir.
Thank you.

676
00:49:12,482 --> 00:49:14,184
Goodbye.
Bye, Father.

677
00:49:20,223 --> 00:49:21,725
God bless you.

678
00:49:24,194 --> 00:49:26,430
I think he
meant that, Admiral.

679
00:49:27,831 --> 00:49:30,334
He wouldn't know
how not to mean it.

680
00:49:54,791 --> 00:49:57,027
Which one of you
is Joe Foss?

681
00:50:05,535 --> 00:50:07,070
That's me, sir.

682
00:50:10,707 --> 00:50:13,877
I've been hearing a lot of
good things about you.

683
00:50:14,444 --> 00:50:16,246
Likewise, Admiral.

684
00:50:16,279 --> 00:50:18,682
<i>NARRATOR: Captain</i>
<i>Joseph Jacob Foss.</i>

685
00:50:18,715 --> 00:50:20,951
<i>First Ace to destroy</i>
<i>as many enemy planes</i>

686
00:50:20,984 --> 00:50:23,754
<i>as Eddie Rickenbacker did</i>
<i>in World War I.</i>

687
00:50:23,787 --> 00:50:27,090
<i>Executive officer of</i>
<i>Squadron WMF-121,</i>

688
00:50:27,124 --> 00:50:29,760
<i>known as</i>
<i>"Joe's Flying Circus."</i>

689
00:50:29,793 --> 00:50:34,765
 <i>In 1955 he will become the</i>
 <i>20th Governor of South Dakota.</i>

690
00:50:34,798 --> 00:50:37,200
Last night's raid
cost us two destroyed,
seven damaged,

691
00:50:37,234 --> 00:50:39,102
but not beyond repair.

692
00:50:40,904 --> 00:50:42,406
How do you feel
about the Zeros?

693
00:50:42,439 --> 00:50:44,541
Well, they've got
a definite edge
in a dogfight.

694
00:50:44,574 --> 00:50:47,244
More maneuverable
and they out-climb us.

695
00:50:48,612 --> 00:50:52,115
Well, you'll be getting the
new Corsairs within two weeks,

696
00:50:52,149 --> 00:50:55,051
and I'll get the P-38's to
the Army as quickly as I can.

697
00:50:55,085 --> 00:50:57,888
That should change
the picture considerably.

698
00:50:57,921 --> 00:50:59,723
We can use a change,
Admiral.

699
00:50:59,756 --> 00:51:01,725
You're doing better than
well with what you have.

700
00:51:01,758 --> 00:51:04,961
But the new stuff should help.
Good to see you.

701
00:51:05,495 --> 00:51:07,030
Thank you, sir.

702
00:51:22,846 --> 00:51:24,381
How's it going?

703
00:51:25,782 --> 00:51:27,717
Great. Just great.

704
00:51:28,718 --> 00:51:31,421
And you can
quote me directly on that.

705
00:51:31,455 --> 00:51:34,124
 <i>NARRATOR: Lieutenant</i>
 <i>Thomas G. Lanphier, Jr.,</i>

706
00:51:34,157 --> 00:51:36,026
<i>100 combat missions.</i>

707
00:51:36,059 --> 00:51:39,930
<i>Shot down seven Jap planes,</i>
<i>destroyed 10 on the ground.</i>

708
00:51:39,963 --> 00:51:42,432
<i>Soloed at the age of 14.</i>

709
00:51:42,466 --> 00:51:45,702
No sleep at night.
Japs coming in,
dropping bombs.

710
00:51:45,735 --> 00:51:47,370
Nothing but mud.

711
00:51:48,305 --> 00:51:49,539
Whoever dreamed
this one up

712
00:51:49,573 --> 00:51:52,809
ought to be hung
from the nearest
palm tree by his thumbs.

713
00:51:52,843 --> 00:51:55,178
If you mean
General Tojo,
I agree.

714
00:51:56,646 --> 00:51:58,849
Be seeing you.
Yeah.

715
00:51:58,882 --> 00:52:01,451
What did you say
your name was?

716
00:52:01,485 --> 00:52:04,688
I didn't say.
But it's Lamphier.
Tom Lamphier.

717
00:52:13,196 --> 00:52:15,732
Thanks. Say,
who the hell was that?

718
00:52:16,933 --> 00:52:20,270
They say his
name is Halsey.

719
00:52:23,440 --> 00:52:24,708
Halsey?

720
00:52:32,749 --> 00:52:35,652
There's nothing wrong
with this chow.

721
00:52:35,685 --> 00:52:38,188
The problem is quantity,
not quality.

722
00:52:40,924 --> 00:52:42,859
Archie, I have an idea...

723
00:52:43,693 --> 00:52:46,196
(RUMBLING)

724
00:52:46,229 --> 00:52:49,699
<i>NARRATOR: Washing Machine</i>
<i>Charlie. A nightly visitor.</i>

725
00:52:49,733 --> 00:52:52,702
 <i>Twin-engines purposely</i>
 <i>out of synchronization.</i>

726
00:52:52,736 --> 00:52:54,070
<i>Bombs small.</i>

727
00:52:54,104 --> 00:52:57,440
<i>Mission, keep the</i>
<i>Allied Forces from sleeping.</i>

728
00:53:00,443 --> 00:53:02,245
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

729
00:53:05,148 --> 00:53:07,050
That his calling card?

730
00:53:08,718 --> 00:53:09,920
There's not much
to worry about,

731
00:53:09,953 --> 00:53:12,722
unless some of his
friends drop by later.

732
00:53:13,590 --> 00:53:16,459
I hope not.
I could use some sleep.

733
00:53:26,570 --> 00:53:28,271
(ALARM BELL RINGS)

734
00:53:30,740 --> 00:53:32,409
(AIR RAID SIRENS WAILING)

735
00:53:40,116 --> 00:53:41,785
Air raid, Admiral.

736
00:53:43,987 --> 00:53:45,889
What's the procedure?

737
00:53:45,922 --> 00:53:48,091
The nearest shelter
until the "All Clear."

738
00:53:51,461 --> 00:53:53,196
And leave here
for a hole in the ground?

739
00:53:54,831 --> 00:53:56,032
I recommend it.

740
00:53:58,168 --> 00:54:00,904
HALSEY: Well, no thanks.

741
00:54:00,937 --> 00:54:02,839
Suit yourself, Admiral.

742
00:54:18,455 --> 00:54:19,823
(EXPLOSION)

743
00:54:27,364 --> 00:54:28,798
(EXPLOSION)

744
00:54:55,158 --> 00:54:57,527
MARINE: Sorry.
No more room here.

745
00:55:12,108 --> 00:55:14,144
HALSEY: Sorry to come
barging in like this.

746
00:55:14,177 --> 00:55:16,379
MARINE: Glad for
the company.

747
00:55:17,180 --> 00:55:19,282
HALSEY: You got
a cigarette?

748
00:55:31,194 --> 00:55:33,596
How long do
these things
usually go on?

749
00:55:33,630 --> 00:55:35,532
An hour.
Sometimes two.

750
00:55:36,866 --> 00:55:38,435
You're new, huh?

751
00:55:40,070 --> 00:55:42,672
Yeah. New.

752
00:55:42,706 --> 00:55:46,176
<i>NARRATOR: The man who</i>
<i>occupies the shelter</i>
<i>is Corporal Joseph Halligan.</i>

753
00:55:46,209 --> 00:55:48,211
<i>Single.</i>
<i>Professional ball player.</i>

754
00:55:48,244 --> 00:55:52,015
<i>A week from now he'll catch</i>
<i>a piece of shrapnel</i>
<i>in his left shoulder.</i>

755
00:55:52,048 --> 00:55:56,453
<i>He'll never get higher</i>
<i>than a Class B league.</i>
<i>He'll blame it on his wound.</i>

756
00:55:57,821 --> 00:55:59,723
It's good to see you,
Archie.
Good to see you, Bill.

757
00:55:59,756 --> 00:56:01,958
And you can count
on all the support
we can give,

758
00:56:01,991 --> 00:56:03,193
as long as I have
one ship.

759
00:56:03,226 --> 00:56:06,062
I know that.
And don't forget
your souvenir.

760
00:56:14,170 --> 00:56:15,472
What's this?

761
00:56:15,505 --> 00:56:17,207
They heard that
you were here, sir.

762
00:56:17,240 --> 00:56:20,543
If you'd just say
a few words, they
would appreciate it.

763
00:56:20,577 --> 00:56:22,579
But, my voice
won't carry that far.

764
00:56:22,612 --> 00:56:24,280
Excuse me,
Admiral.

765
00:56:27,584 --> 00:56:29,586
We have
a microphone, sir.

766
00:56:32,922 --> 00:56:36,392
<i>I... I guess...</i>

767
00:56:36,426 --> 00:56:38,261
(FEEDBACK SCREECHING)

768
00:56:39,596 --> 00:56:40,663
<i>I got...</i>

769
00:56:40,697 --> 00:56:42,132
(FEEDBACK)

770
00:56:42,165 --> 00:56:44,167
<i>What the hell's</i>
<i>the matter</i>
<i>with this thing?</i>

771
00:56:44,200 --> 00:56:45,602
(ALL LAUGH)

772
00:56:49,639 --> 00:56:54,511
<i>I guess you want to know</i>
<i>why we're hanging on to</i>
<i>this island.</i>

773
00:56:54,544 --> 00:57:00,250
<i>Well, the Jap has had</i>
<i>everything his own way</i>
<i>since the start of this war.</i>

774
00:57:00,283 --> 00:57:04,754
<i>He's pushed us back across</i>
<i>thousands of miles of ocean</i>

775
00:57:04,788 --> 00:57:10,026
<i>and through countless islands</i>
<i>until the world began to think</i>
<i>that he couldn't be stopped.</i>

776
00:57:11,060 --> 00:57:13,029
<i>Well, he's been stopped.</i>

777
00:57:13,897 --> 00:57:16,232
<i>Right here by you.</i>

778
00:57:17,300 --> 00:57:20,270
<i>Right here on</i>
<i>this stinking island.</i>

779
00:57:20,303 --> 00:57:22,839
<i>You've beaten him</i>
<i>at his own game.</i>

780
00:57:22,872 --> 00:57:26,609
<i>You've thrown back everything</i>
<i>that he's tossed at you.</i>

781
00:57:26,643 --> 00:57:29,946
<i>You men,</i>
<i>and you alone have stopped</i>

782
00:57:29,979 --> 00:57:32,882
 <i>the greatest over-water</i>
 <i>offensive in history.</i>

783
00:57:33,917 --> 00:57:36,886
<i>You, by what you've done,</i>

784
00:57:36,920 --> 00:57:41,524
<i>have made this the most</i>
<i>important piece of real estate</i>
<i>in the entire Pacific.</i>

785
00:57:42,192 --> 00:57:43,893
<i>Now, you see this?</i>

786
00:57:45,028 --> 00:57:48,531
 <i>This is Admiral Yamamoto's</i>
 <i>plan for the ceremony</i>

787
00:57:50,266 --> 00:57:53,369
<i>that was to follow</i>
<i>our surrender of Guadalcanal.</i>

788
00:57:55,104 --> 00:57:57,540
<i>It tells us</i>
<i>how we're to behave,</i>

789
00:58:00,009 --> 00:58:02,312
<i>indicates the spot,</i>

790
00:58:02,345 --> 00:58:04,881
<i>specifies where</i>
<i>we're to stand.</i>

791
00:58:07,717 --> 00:58:11,254
<i>General Vandergrift gave me</i>
<i>this captured document</i>

792
00:58:12,388 --> 00:58:13,890
<i>as a souvenir.</i>

793
00:58:16,025 --> 00:58:20,096
<i>Somehow I think</i>
<i>you'd appreciate it more.</i>

794
00:58:26,469 --> 00:58:28,705
Nail it to that tree.
Yes, sir.

795
00:58:44,220 --> 00:58:46,289
(MIKUMA SPEAKING JAPANESE)

796
00:58:51,494 --> 00:58:55,231
<i>NARRATOR: Captain</i>
<i>Sentaro Mikuma.</i>
<i>Operations officer.</i>

797
00:58:55,265 --> 00:58:59,802
<i>He has a wife, two children</i>
<i>and a successful law practice</i>
<i>in Yokohama.</i>

798
00:58:59,836 --> 00:59:02,805
 <i>Each morning he conducts</i>
 <i>this briefing session.</i>

799
00:59:02,839 --> 00:59:06,242
<i>Today's report contains</i>
<i>a couple of unpleasant items.</i>

800
00:59:06,276 --> 00:59:10,613
<i>In the past 24 hours,</i>
<i>the Japanese have lost</i>
<i>11 bombers and eight fighters</i>

801
00:59:10,647 --> 00:59:15,752
<i>and encountered increased</i>
<i>resistance on the ground</i>
<i>at Guadalcanal.</i>

802
00:59:15,785 --> 00:59:21,057
<i>Vice Admiral Boshiroshima</i>
<i>asks Captain Mikuma to account</i>
<i>for this increased resistance.</i>

803
00:59:21,090 --> 00:59:25,895
<i>Mikuma attributes it</i>
<i>to Admiral Halsey's</i>
<i>visit there four days ago.</i>

804
00:59:25,929 --> 00:59:28,231
<i>Japanese intelligence knows</i>
<i>that in two weeks</i>

805
00:59:28,264 --> 00:59:32,802
<i>American pilots on Guadalcanal</i>
<i>will receive new Corsair</i>
<i>and P-38 fighters.</i>

806
00:59:34,470 --> 00:59:36,339
<i>Rear Admiral Kobe</i>
<i>has just predicted</i>

807
00:59:36,372 --> 00:59:39,676
<i>that in two weeks</i>
<i>there will be nothing</i>
<i>for them to land on.</i>

808
00:59:39,709 --> 00:59:42,145
<i>Everyone finds this amusing.</i>

809
00:59:42,178 --> 00:59:44,113
<i>Well, almost everyone.</i>

810
00:59:45,882 --> 00:59:48,651
<i>Yamamoto will tolerate</i>
<i>no more postponements.</i>

811
00:59:48,685 --> 00:59:51,754
<i>He outlines a blueprint</i>
<i>to be followed at all costs.</i>

812
00:59:51,788 --> 00:59:54,624
<i>On October 22nd,</i>
<i>he will take Henderson Field.</i>

813
00:59:54,657 --> 00:59:58,194
<i>On October 23rd,</i>
<i>he will land troops</i>
<i>under heavy air cover.</i>

814
00:59:58,227 --> 01:00:02,865
<i>On October 24th, his planes</i>
<i>will commence operations</i>
<i>from Henderson Field.</i>

815
01:00:02,899 --> 01:00:05,201
<i>On October 25th,</i>
<i>his battleships, Cruisers</i>

816
01:00:05,234 --> 01:00:08,137
 <i>and carriers will engage</i>
 <i>the United States naval forces</i>

817
01:00:08,171 --> 01:00:12,342
<i>and maintain contact until</i>
<i>those forces are obliterated.</i>

818
01:00:12,375 --> 01:00:15,678
<i>The occupation and surrender</i>
<i>of Guadalcanal will follow.</i>

819
01:00:15,712 --> 01:00:19,482
<i>Until that is accomplished</i>
<i>he cares to hear</i>
<i>no more laughter.</i>

820
01:00:21,651 --> 01:00:25,688
PULASKI: A patrol plane
has spotted an enemy fleet
sailing south from Truk,

821
01:00:25,722 --> 01:00:29,158
four carriers,
four battleships,
eighteen cruisers.

822
01:00:29,192 --> 01:00:34,030
In addition, we have coast
watcher reports of Japanese
transports and auxiliaries,

823
01:00:34,063 --> 01:00:37,467
plus cruiser escort,
moving down the Slot
from Rabul.

824
01:00:37,500 --> 01:00:39,202
Looks like
the start.
Yes, sir.

825
01:00:39,235 --> 01:00:41,904
I don't get it.
How can Yamamoto
launch an attack

826
01:00:41,938 --> 01:00:44,640
while we still have
land based air
on Guadalcanal?

827
01:00:44,674 --> 01:00:48,678
He's anticipating.
By the time his fleet
moves down to this point,

828
01:00:49,679 --> 01:00:51,981
he assumes
he'll have Henderson Field.

829
01:00:52,015 --> 01:00:54,484
That means Vandergrift
can look forward
to increased pressure.

830
01:00:54,517 --> 01:00:58,755
And we can look forward
to the 25th or the 26th
at the outside,

831
01:00:58,788 --> 01:01:00,356
being Zero day.

832
01:01:02,091 --> 01:01:05,194
What's the matter, Frank?

833
01:01:05,228 --> 01:01:08,431
I guess I didn't expect
them to try anything
like this so soon.

834
01:01:08,464 --> 01:01:10,233
Neither did I.

835
01:01:10,266 --> 01:01:14,704
We have lost the initiative
for the moment,
but I propose to get it back.

836
01:01:14,737 --> 01:01:17,707
The
<i>Hornet</i>
 and
the
<i>Enterprise</i>
 will throw
the first punch.

837
01:01:17,740 --> 01:01:20,276
Two carriers against
his whole fleet?
Umm-hmm.

838
01:01:20,309 --> 01:01:21,677
That's it, exactly.

839
01:01:21,711 --> 01:01:25,048
Don't forget,
he doesn't know where
our carriers are.

840
01:01:25,081 --> 01:01:26,682
And the trick will be
to keep him guessing.

841
01:01:26,716 --> 01:01:28,017
It could work.

842
01:01:28,051 --> 01:01:30,920
If Kincaid and Murray
made a wide sweep

843
01:01:30,953 --> 01:01:34,023
east of
the Santa Cruz Islands,
beyond their search range,

844
01:01:34,057 --> 01:01:37,360
and then cut back in time,
our carriers could
hit them coming in.

845
01:01:37,393 --> 01:01:42,198
Meanwhile we give
Guadalcanal close support
with our cruiser task force.

846
01:01:42,231 --> 01:01:43,700
What do you think,
Mike?

847
01:01:43,733 --> 01:01:45,134
One thing's sure,
Admiral.

848
01:01:45,168 --> 01:01:48,538
He'll never expect
you to come out
looking for him.

849
01:01:48,571 --> 01:01:50,807
There's an old saying,

850
01:01:50,840 --> 01:01:56,446
"No Captain can do very wrong
if he places his ship
alongside that of an enemy."

851
01:01:59,082 --> 01:02:02,118
Well, that'll
hold you
for six months.

852
01:02:02,151 --> 01:02:04,587
Let me have
the alcohol,
will you?

853
01:02:05,755 --> 01:02:08,191
Well, Andy,
looks like
you're next.

854
01:02:12,095 --> 01:02:13,229
I want to see you,
Andy.

855
01:02:13,262 --> 01:02:16,299
(GASPS) Yes, sir.

856
01:02:16,332 --> 01:02:18,734
Well, as long as you're here,
sir, if you'll just
roll up your sleeve...

857
01:02:18,768 --> 01:02:20,236
No, better set up
an appointment, Doc.

858
01:02:20,269 --> 01:02:22,004
Some day when
I have more time.

859
01:02:22,038 --> 01:02:23,740
Ah, come in when
you're through
here, Andy.

860
01:02:23,773 --> 01:02:25,041
Yes, sir.

861
01:02:32,882 --> 01:02:34,450
Come in, Andy.

862
01:02:36,652 --> 01:02:38,688
Captain Bailey's
been given command
of the
<i>Enterprise.</i>

863
01:02:38,721 --> 01:02:41,357
And now he's trying
to steal a member
of my staff

864
01:02:41,390 --> 01:02:43,960
for one of his fighter
squadron commanders,
you know anything about it?

865
01:02:43,993 --> 01:02:45,862
No, sir.

866
01:02:45,895 --> 01:02:48,631
You been doing
a little politicking?
Sir?

867
01:02:49,999 --> 01:02:51,267
He asked for you
by name.

868
01:02:51,300 --> 01:02:52,602
Oh, oh,
is that a fact?

869
01:02:52,635 --> 01:02:53,936
Yes, that's a fact.

870
01:02:53,970 --> 01:02:55,671
Well, sir,
I'd certainly
hate to leave you,

871
01:02:55,705 --> 01:02:58,207
but if Captain Bailey
really needs me,
why I'm willing to go.

872
01:02:58,241 --> 01:02:59,375
I'll bet you are,

873
01:02:59,408 --> 01:03:01,177
I hear the big "E's"
gonna see action
in three days.

874
01:03:01,210 --> 01:03:03,679
And if you're not
there, you're gonna
be heart-broken.

875
01:03:03,713 --> 01:03:05,348
Yes, sir.

876
01:03:05,381 --> 01:03:08,184
Well, you'll get
your crack
at combat, Andy.

877
01:03:08,217 --> 01:03:10,620
But right now,
I don't think much
of your timing.

878
01:03:10,653 --> 01:03:13,723
But, sir, what...
What purpose
do I serve here?

879
01:03:13,756 --> 01:03:16,893
Well, unfortunately
I'm used to you.

880
01:03:16,926 --> 01:03:19,829
Well, sir, if...
If that's all, I...

881
01:03:20,830 --> 01:03:22,465
Oh, all right,
all right, all right,

882
01:03:22,498 --> 01:03:25,401
on second thought,
you've been a pretty
sorry excuse for an aide,

883
01:03:25,434 --> 01:03:27,737
so Captain Bailey
can have you.

884
01:03:27,770 --> 01:03:29,639
Thank you.
Thank you very much, sir.
Thank you.

885
01:03:29,672 --> 01:03:30,740
Go on,
get out of here.

886
01:03:30,773 --> 01:03:32,575
Yes, sir.
Good night, sir.

887
01:03:32,608 --> 01:03:36,512
Oh... Sir, I...
I wondered if...

888
01:03:36,546 --> 01:03:39,081
If I could ask
a special favor.

889
01:03:39,115 --> 01:03:40,583
Yes, sure, Andy.

890
01:03:40,616 --> 01:03:43,186
Well, sir, I realize
I haven't been the world's
best aide, in many ways

891
01:03:43,219 --> 01:03:46,722
I've slipped up on my duty,
but, sir, my conscience
would be a mite clearer

892
01:03:46,756 --> 01:03:51,827
if I could leave here knowing
that I had at least performed
one part of my assignment.

893
01:03:51,861 --> 01:03:53,296
What's that?

894
01:03:55,298 --> 01:03:59,402
Well, sir,
it was my duty to see
that you got your shots.

895
01:04:05,374 --> 01:04:08,211
Is this in the nature
of one last request?

896
01:04:08,778 --> 01:04:10,379
Well, it's a...

897
01:04:11,881 --> 01:04:13,216
All right.

898
01:04:14,717 --> 01:04:16,519
Get Doc Key.

899
01:04:16,552 --> 01:04:19,222
Yes, sir. Aye, aye, sir.

900
01:04:21,557 --> 01:04:24,694
I'm going after Doc Key.
The Admiral's gonna
take his shots.

901
01:04:24,727 --> 01:04:26,295
If anybody wants me,
I've gone for Doc Key.

902
01:04:26,329 --> 01:04:28,865
The Admiral's gonna
take his shots.

903
01:04:28,898 --> 01:04:31,334
The Admiral's gonna
take his shots.

904
01:04:36,739 --> 01:04:39,375
I never saw so much
commotion about
a couple of shots.

905
01:04:39,408 --> 01:04:41,744
Not just a couple,
Admiral. Five.

906
01:04:42,745 --> 01:04:44,780
Five?
Five, sir.

907
01:04:44,814 --> 01:04:47,049
Watch out for
the hook, sir.

908
01:04:47,083 --> 01:04:48,417
(ALL LAUGH)

909
01:04:50,753 --> 01:04:53,322
Very funny. Very funny.

910
01:04:54,090 --> 01:04:55,825
Here comes number 1.

911
01:05:01,797 --> 01:05:03,833
DR. KEY: Now,
here comes number 2.

912
01:05:09,705 --> 01:05:11,707
This'll be number three.

913
01:05:15,945 --> 01:05:19,181
<i>NARRATOR: Aboard his flagship,</i>
<i>Admiral Yamamoto</i>
<i>expresses anxiety</i>

914
01:05:19,215 --> 01:05:23,286
<i>over the failure of his</i>
<i>search planes to locate</i>
<i>the American carriers.</i>

915
01:05:23,319 --> 01:05:26,088
 <i>At midnight, he issues</i>
 <i>the following orders...</i>

916
01:05:26,122 --> 01:05:30,760
<i>"Aircraft will continue</i>
<i>to search and track regardless</i>
<i>of weather or enemy planes,</i>

917
01:05:30,793 --> 01:05:34,930
<i>"in an attempt to discover</i>
<i>the size and nature</i>
<i>of enemy forces.</i>

918
01:05:34,964 --> 01:05:38,000
<i>"When the position</i>
<i>of the American forces</i>
<i>has been discovered,</i>

919
01:05:38,034 --> 01:05:41,771
<i>"there is a great likelihood</i>
<i>of a sea battle</i>
<i>northeast of the Solomons.</i>

920
01:05:41,804 --> 01:05:45,007
<i>"The battle for Guadalcanal</i>
<i>still continues."</i>

921
01:05:53,082 --> 01:05:55,017
Fresh PBY contact,
sir.

922
01:05:55,051 --> 01:05:58,287
They report one
large carrier
and six other vessels

923
01:05:58,321 --> 01:06:00,756
200 miles away
on the same bearing.

924
01:06:20,276 --> 01:06:23,312
Issue these orders
to all task force
commanders immediately.

925
01:06:23,346 --> 01:06:24,981
Is this all, sir?

926
01:06:25,014 --> 01:06:26,182
That's all.

927
01:06:26,215 --> 01:06:28,484
Yes, sir.

928
01:06:28,517 --> 01:06:31,554
<i>NARRATOR: The order reads,</i>
<i>"Attack, repeat, attack."</i>

929
01:06:31,587 --> 01:06:33,823
<i>17 years later he was to say,</i>

930
01:06:33,856 --> 01:06:38,227
<i>"It is very easy to order</i>
<i>an attack if you don't have</i>
<i>to do the attacking."</i>

931
01:06:38,260 --> 01:06:39,628
<i>But is it?</i>

932
01:07:32,815 --> 01:07:34,550
<i>Aboard Admiral</i>
<i>Yamamoto's flagship</i>

933
01:07:34,583 --> 01:07:36,919
<i>there is a small</i>
<i>celebration taking place.</i>

934
01:07:36,952 --> 01:07:38,888
<i>Admiral Kobe is a teetotaler.</i>

935
01:07:38,921 --> 01:07:41,257
<i>But the news demands</i>
<i>he break a rule.</i>

936
01:07:41,290 --> 01:07:43,492
<i>They drink to the sinking</i>
<i>of the</i>
 Hornet.

937
01:07:43,526 --> 01:07:45,027
<i>It was from decks</i>
<i>of the</i>
 Hornet

938
01:07:45,060 --> 01:07:48,130
<i>that Halsey dispatched</i>
<i>Doolittle's planes</i>
<i>against Tokyo.</i>

939
01:07:48,164 --> 01:07:52,268
<i>It was Yamamoto who was blamed</i>
<i>when they penetrated</i>
<i>the island's defenses.</i>

940
01:07:52,301 --> 01:07:56,906
<i>This adds savor to the drink,</i>
<i>personal triumph</i>
<i>to the victory.</i>

941
01:07:56,939 --> 01:08:00,743
We lost the
<i>Hornet.</i>
They damaged
the
<i>Enterprise.</i>

942
01:08:00,776 --> 01:08:04,146
We lost 283 men,
killed or missing.

943
01:08:05,781 --> 01:08:09,452
Aircraft,
they lost a minimum
of a hundred.

944
01:08:09,485 --> 01:08:15,458
Against that,
our carrier plane losses,
from all causes, were 74.

945
01:08:18,127 --> 01:08:20,029
That it?
That's it, sir.

946
01:08:21,897 --> 01:08:23,466
Any discussion?

947
01:08:24,867 --> 01:08:26,068
Harry?

948
01:08:26,969 --> 01:08:29,538
What's there to say,
sir?

949
01:08:29,572 --> 01:08:32,608
We got the
short end
of the stick.

950
01:08:32,641 --> 01:08:35,811
Tactically, yes.
Strategically, no.

951
01:08:36,745 --> 01:08:38,914
But we lost
the
<i>Hornet,</i>
 sir.

952
01:08:40,249 --> 01:08:42,151
What was our objective?

953
01:08:42,852 --> 01:08:47,289
To hang on to Guadalcanal.

954
01:08:47,323 --> 01:08:51,894
I'm calling your attention
to the fact that the Marines
are still doing just that.

955
01:08:51,927 --> 01:08:55,197
Yes, sir,
but the Japanese fleet
is still in the area.

956
01:08:55,231 --> 01:08:56,799
We're wide open.

957
01:08:56,832 --> 01:08:58,467
Harry's right, sir.

958
01:08:58,501 --> 01:09:02,171
If they follow up today,
we have nothing
to stop them with.

959
01:09:02,671 --> 01:09:03,873
Sir...

960
01:09:04,907 --> 01:09:07,009
Go on.

961
01:09:07,042 --> 01:09:10,145
I think it's up to
the Staff to recommend
emergency measures

962
01:09:10,179 --> 01:09:13,382
in the event we're forced
to evacuate Guadalcanal.

963
01:09:16,619 --> 01:09:18,354
You feel that way?

964
01:09:23,025 --> 01:09:26,562
It's true
that if the Japs
follow up today,

965
01:09:28,030 --> 01:09:30,866
and their fleet keeps
coming down the slot,

966
01:09:31,767 --> 01:09:33,536
we can't stop them.

967
01:09:35,371 --> 01:09:38,340
But I don't think
they'll do that.

968
01:09:38,374 --> 01:09:42,178
With a hundred planes
and pilots lost,

969
01:09:42,211 --> 01:09:46,015
the air groups
aboard those Jap carriers
have been cut to pieces.

970
01:09:46,048 --> 01:09:48,951
And why should they
come further south

971
01:09:48,984 --> 01:09:52,688
to place themselves
under land-based air attack?

972
01:09:52,721 --> 01:09:55,991
And a second thing,
in our favor,
the record.

973
01:09:57,126 --> 01:09:58,527
Ever since Pearl Harbor,

974
01:09:58,561 --> 01:10:02,798
the Japs have
consistently failed
to follow up an advance.

975
01:10:02,831 --> 01:10:07,603
I'm gambling that
they won't break the habit.

976
01:10:07,636 --> 01:10:10,372
We could still arrange
evacuation measures
for insurance.

977
01:10:10,406 --> 01:10:12,374
No. No.

978
01:10:12,408 --> 01:10:16,378
If they pick up the hint
that we're even
contemplating evacuation,

979
01:10:16,412 --> 01:10:19,782
they'll be down here
like vultures.

980
01:10:19,815 --> 01:10:22,718
In other words,
we lash down
the safety valves.

981
01:10:22,751 --> 01:10:24,420
We lash them down.

982
01:10:26,021 --> 01:10:30,159
I want all the senior
commanders
of the services

983
01:10:30,192 --> 01:10:34,897
to pool their
mechanics in an
emergency repair force

984
01:10:34,930 --> 01:10:38,634
and work around the clock
to restore ship damage,

985
01:10:39,702 --> 01:10:41,870
particularly the
<i>Enterprise.</i>

986
01:10:45,107 --> 01:10:49,278
Well, as far as
I'm concerned, gentlemen,
the battle was a stand-off.

987
01:10:50,346 --> 01:10:52,348
Just when we needed one.

988
01:11:12,001 --> 01:11:16,105
"A PBY contact at 1400

989
01:11:16,138 --> 01:11:21,810
"reports the enemy fleet
in a general retirement
toward Truk."

990
01:11:29,151 --> 01:11:33,355
<i>NARRATOR: On board</i>
<i>the</i>
 Enterprise,
<i>Andy Lowe</i>
<i>talks to some of his own men</i>

991
01:11:33,389 --> 01:11:36,158
<i>and some of the survivors</i>
<i>of the</i>
 Hornet.

992
01:11:37,326 --> 01:11:39,428
<i>It has not been an easy day.</i>

993
01:12:03,352 --> 01:12:04,420
Howdy.

994
01:12:04,453 --> 01:12:06,488
You Andy Lowe?

995
01:12:06,522 --> 01:12:08,691
That's right.
I was told
to double up with you.

996
01:12:08,724 --> 01:12:10,859
Oh, well,
glad to have you.

997
01:12:11,560 --> 01:12:13,996
Whose bunk was that?

998
01:12:14,029 --> 01:12:15,864
A fellow by the name
of Cerella.

999
01:12:15,898 --> 01:12:16,932
Dead?

1000
01:12:16,965 --> 01:12:18,534
He's missing.
Same difference.

1001
01:12:18,567 --> 01:12:21,537
Well, now I wouldn't
say that.
Well, I would.

1002
01:12:30,913 --> 01:12:34,450
I guess you've got
quite a few extra bunks
on the
<i>Enterprise</i>
 tonight.

1003
01:12:34,483 --> 01:12:36,218
Yeah, quite a few.

1004
01:12:36,985 --> 01:12:38,787
Did he have a family.
Huh?

1005
01:12:38,821 --> 01:12:41,557
The man who used
to bunk up there,
did he have a family?

1006
01:12:41,590 --> 01:12:42,791
No, no.

1007
01:12:44,460 --> 01:12:46,695
Do you mind
if I use your typewriter?

1008
01:12:46,729 --> 01:12:48,263
Help yourself.

1009
01:12:56,472 --> 01:13:00,375
I... I didn't get
your name.

1010
01:13:00,409 --> 01:13:02,745
Roy Webb.
Oh, yeah.

1011
01:13:02,778 --> 01:13:05,414
Aren't you
Squadron Commander
of the F-11?

1012
01:13:05,447 --> 01:13:07,683
I won't be
when I finish this.

1013
01:13:08,417 --> 01:13:10,886
I lost half my
squadron today.

1014
01:13:10,919 --> 01:13:13,722
One half of an
entire squadron.

1015
01:13:13,756 --> 01:13:16,792
Nine planes. Nine men.

1016
01:13:19,928 --> 01:13:21,797
Making out
a strike report?

1017
01:13:21,830 --> 01:13:23,599
No.

1018
01:13:23,632 --> 01:13:26,935
From the look on your face,
I figure it's no love letter.

1019
01:13:26,969 --> 01:13:30,139
I'm asking to be
relieved of command.

1020
01:13:30,172 --> 01:13:33,709
Oh, well,
sooner or later we all
need a rest from flying.

1021
01:13:34,777 --> 01:13:37,346
Well, I don't need
a rest from flying.

1022
01:13:37,379 --> 01:13:39,481
I'll fly combat
again tomorrow.

1023
01:13:39,515 --> 01:13:42,918
I just do not want
to command.

1024
01:13:42,951 --> 01:13:46,488
I lost some guys today.
We all did.
It wasn't your fault.

1025
01:13:46,522 --> 01:13:48,357
Now how can you tell?

1026
01:13:52,127 --> 01:13:53,462
You know, my mother
said to me once,

1027
01:13:53,495 --> 01:13:57,199
she said, "Never make
an important decision
when I was tired."

1028
01:13:58,300 --> 01:14:01,136
I found that to be
a good piece of advice.

1029
01:14:01,670 --> 01:14:03,572
I know what I'm doing.

1030
01:14:18,387 --> 01:14:20,122
The Big "E."

1031
01:14:20,155 --> 01:14:23,125
Yes, sir,
she brought us home.

1032
01:14:23,158 --> 01:14:24,960
We've fixed most of
the leaks
in the oil tanks,

1033
01:14:24,993 --> 01:14:27,463
but the damage
to the forward
elevator's pretty bad.

1034
01:14:27,496 --> 01:14:28,964
Admiral.

1035
01:14:28,997 --> 01:14:31,033
Andy.
How are you?

1036
01:14:31,066 --> 01:14:32,301
Very good, sir.

1037
01:14:32,334 --> 01:14:33,402
Good evening, sir.
Evening.

1038
01:14:33,435 --> 01:14:35,671
Congratulations
on those two Zeros.
Thank you.

1039
01:14:35,704 --> 01:14:38,674
He splashed
three of them, sir.

1040
01:14:38,707 --> 01:14:40,509
If you'll excuse me,
Admiral.
Certainly.

1041
01:14:40,542 --> 01:14:42,578
Keep after them, Bill.

1042
01:14:42,611 --> 01:14:46,415
Well, I hear your relief
is showing up.

1043
01:14:46,448 --> 01:14:49,485
Maybe you can tell me
something about
a Commander Roy Webb?

1044
01:14:49,518 --> 01:14:51,053
Oh, yes sir.
He's...

1045
01:14:51,086 --> 01:14:53,689
He's Squadron Commander
on the
<i>Hornet.</i>

1046
01:14:54,523 --> 01:14:56,325
Would he fit in?

1047
01:14:56,358 --> 01:14:58,327
Well, he'd make
an okay pilot for you, sir.

1048
01:14:58,360 --> 01:15:01,129
He's...
He's experienced,
he's available.

1049
01:15:02,531 --> 01:15:04,867
We need Squadron
Commanders.

1050
01:15:04,900 --> 01:15:06,902
Why is he available?

1051
01:15:06,935 --> 01:15:11,473
Well, right at this time,
the pilots on the
<i>Hornet</i>
have no ship, sir.

1052
01:15:12,875 --> 01:15:15,510
They'll be reassigned,
though.

1053
01:15:15,544 --> 01:15:19,214
Andy, I'd like
a straight answer.

1054
01:15:21,483 --> 01:15:24,953
Well, the fact is,
Admiral, Webb asked
to be detached.

1055
01:15:25,787 --> 01:15:28,056
Said he was unfit
for command.

1056
01:15:29,758 --> 01:15:30,859
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1057
01:15:30,893 --> 01:15:32,160
Come in.

1058
01:15:34,229 --> 01:15:36,198
Lieutenant Commander Webb
to see you, sir.

1059
01:15:36,231 --> 01:15:37,633
Send him in.

1060
01:15:44,940 --> 01:15:46,241
Webb?
Sir.

1061
01:15:47,676 --> 01:15:51,380
I need an aide
who can double
as my pilot.

1062
01:15:51,413 --> 01:15:55,817
Your name has been
submitted. How do you
feel about the job?

1063
01:15:55,851 --> 01:16:00,422
I'd be honored, sir.
Frankly, I think
I belong in combat.

1064
01:16:00,455 --> 01:16:03,292
Well, according to this,
you asked to be relieved.

1065
01:16:03,325 --> 01:16:06,028
Only from command, sir.
Not from combat.

1066
01:16:08,263 --> 01:16:10,432
I've looked at your record,
it's a good one.

1067
01:16:10,465 --> 01:16:11,867
Navy Cross.

1068
01:16:13,268 --> 01:16:15,938
Every job they gave you,
you did well.

1069
01:16:17,172 --> 01:16:18,740
What happened?

1070
01:16:18,774 --> 01:16:21,443
Sir, I just can't give
any more orders.

1071
01:16:21,476 --> 01:16:23,979
Well, you've been
cutting it all right.

1072
01:16:24,012 --> 01:16:26,181
As a Squadron Commander,
yes, sir.

1073
01:16:26,214 --> 01:16:27,583
Now I'm Senior.

1074
01:16:27,616 --> 01:16:29,484
The Air Group Commander
is in the hospital.

1075
01:16:29,518 --> 01:16:32,487
If he doesn't get well,
I'll be next in line
for his job.

1076
01:16:32,521 --> 01:16:34,456
You don't want
the responsibility?

1077
01:16:34,489 --> 01:16:35,791
No, sir.

1078
01:16:36,725 --> 01:16:37,960
That's normal.

1079
01:16:37,993 --> 01:16:41,129
Sir, I don't think
you have the whole...
Sit down.

1080
01:16:44,900 --> 01:16:48,737
I can think of
some wonderful speeches
I could make right now.

1081
01:16:50,172 --> 01:16:53,442
Probably have
both of us in tears.

1082
01:16:53,475 --> 01:16:56,878
But I just don't
have the time for
such performances.

1083
01:16:57,679 --> 01:16:58,914
Webb...

1084
01:17:00,649 --> 01:17:03,452
Where do you think our
group commanders come from?

1085
01:17:03,485 --> 01:17:07,623
I don't know, sir.
All I do know is that
I'm not the man for the job.

1086
01:17:07,656 --> 01:17:10,158
You think the job requires
a great man?

1087
01:17:10,192 --> 01:17:13,528
Yes, sir.
Well, I have news for you.

1088
01:17:13,562 --> 01:17:15,397
There aren't any great men.

1089
01:17:15,430 --> 01:17:16,698
There are just
great challenges

1090
01:17:16,732 --> 01:17:18,800
that ordinary men
like you and me

1091
01:17:18,834 --> 01:17:21,870
are forced
by circumstances to meet.

1092
01:17:21,903 --> 01:17:25,507
Now, you've proved
you can get the job done.

1093
01:17:25,540 --> 01:17:28,076
You're hooked
by your own record.

1094
01:17:28,110 --> 01:17:32,147
In short,
you don't have any choice.

1095
01:17:32,180 --> 01:17:34,616
Sir, I lost
nine planes yesterday.

1096
01:17:36,685 --> 01:17:42,657
I lost those same
nine planes
and 17 others to boot,

1097
01:17:42,691 --> 01:17:47,896
plus one destroyer,
two submarines
with all hands,

1098
01:17:47,929 --> 01:17:52,868
two LST's, and God knows
how many ground troops.

1099
01:17:52,901 --> 01:17:54,903
Do you want me to go on?

1100
01:17:57,205 --> 01:17:58,440
No, sir.

1101
01:18:00,609 --> 01:18:04,746
I guess I... I just had
the feeling I was alone.

1102
01:18:07,049 --> 01:18:10,419
You were,
and you will be.

1103
01:18:14,056 --> 01:18:16,291
Good luck, Roy.
Thank you, sir.

1104
01:18:22,397 --> 01:18:23,932
You better
step on it, Frank.
The boat's waiting

1105
01:18:23,965 --> 01:18:25,367
and the old man's
raring to go.

1106
01:18:25,400 --> 01:18:27,702
What do you mean?
It's your turn today,

1107
01:18:27,736 --> 01:18:30,238
I swam a mile
with him Tuesday.
It's Murphy's turn.

1108
01:18:30,272 --> 01:18:31,573
Murphy's pulling OD.

1109
01:18:31,606 --> 01:18:34,209
So that makes it
your turn.

1110
01:18:34,242 --> 01:18:36,578
Look, I'm still
waterlogged
from Tuesday.

1111
01:18:36,611 --> 01:18:38,613
The Chaplain's
right down the way.

1112
01:18:38,647 --> 01:18:41,717
Doc, couldn't you
take him today?

1113
01:18:41,750 --> 01:18:43,819
Well,
for a consideration.

1114
01:18:43,852 --> 01:18:46,588
Like a...
Like a pint
of scotch?

1115
01:18:46,621 --> 01:18:48,123
Like a fifth?

1116
01:18:49,691 --> 01:18:51,159
It's a deal.

1117
01:18:51,193 --> 01:18:52,294
(ALL LAUGH)

1118
01:19:13,715 --> 01:19:16,685
Nice work, Doc.
Nice work.

1119
01:19:16,718 --> 01:19:18,253
Where's the old man?

1120
01:19:18,286 --> 01:19:20,355
Well, he's half way
to Japan the last time
I saw him

1121
01:19:20,388 --> 01:19:22,257
and still going
strong.

1122
01:19:22,290 --> 01:19:26,428
I said to him,
"Admiral, I think
we've gone far enough.

1123
01:19:26,461 --> 01:19:28,763
"I think it's time
we turned around
and went back."

1124
01:19:28,797 --> 01:19:30,966
He said, "Is that
a medical opinion?"

1125
01:19:30,999 --> 01:19:32,634
I said, "No, sir.

1126
01:19:32,667 --> 01:19:35,937
"It's just the opinion
of a drowning man."

1127
01:19:35,971 --> 01:19:37,105
Doc, I'll make
a deal with you.

1128
01:19:37,139 --> 01:19:38,707
You give me back
my fifth of Scotch,

1129
01:19:38,740 --> 01:19:40,609
I'll give you
some artificial
respiration.

1130
01:19:40,642 --> 01:19:43,612
He's coming in now.
Look at him
kick and splash.

1131
01:19:43,645 --> 01:19:46,348
I wouldn't be
surprised if
he's part walrus.

1132
01:19:46,381 --> 01:19:47,682
I'll tell you
one thing,

1133
01:19:47,716 --> 01:19:50,218
I go with him again,
it's gonna be in
a row boat.

1134
01:19:50,252 --> 01:19:51,953
Quitting so soon,
sir?

1135
01:19:51,987 --> 01:19:54,990
HALSEY: No.
Just coming in
for a new partner.

1136
01:19:59,728 --> 01:20:03,098
Nothing like a...
Like a good swim
for what ails you.

1137
01:20:03,598 --> 01:20:05,000
Eh, Doc?

1138
01:20:05,033 --> 01:20:08,503
A man can't be
forced to testify
against himself, sir.

1139
01:20:11,506 --> 01:20:13,008
Where's Andy?

1140
01:20:13,408 --> 01:20:14,943
Beach combing.

1141
01:20:19,080 --> 01:20:20,549
(LAUGHING)

1142
01:20:20,582 --> 01:20:23,852
What do you bet
they both come
from his home town?

1143
01:20:26,721 --> 01:20:28,356
A beautiful day.

1144
01:20:29,558 --> 01:20:30,926
Clear sky.

1145
01:20:33,395 --> 01:20:35,430
Not a ship
on the horizon.

1146
01:20:37,432 --> 01:20:40,101
Almost make you forget
there's a war on.

1147
01:20:40,135 --> 01:20:41,436
Yes, sir.

1148
01:20:45,473 --> 01:20:48,777
How soon do you
think Yamamoto
will be back, Mike?

1149
01:20:51,479 --> 01:20:53,081
Two weeks, sir.

1150
01:20:54,549 --> 01:20:57,452
That's, uh,
11 November.

1151
01:20:58,119 --> 01:20:59,888
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

1152
01:21:01,289 --> 01:21:04,426
 <i>NARRATOR: Kobe proposes</i>
 <i>11 November as Zero day.</i>

1153
01:21:05,894 --> 01:21:07,629
<i>The Admiral agrees.</i>

1154
01:21:09,397 --> 01:21:12,867
<i>Yamamoto is ready for another</i>
<i>assault against Guadalcanal.</i>

1155
01:21:12,901 --> 01:21:15,070
<i>Everything he has</i>
<i>will go into this effort.</i>

1156
01:21:15,103 --> 01:21:19,274
<i>Land, sea, air, the Allies</i>
<i>are everywhere out-numbered.</i>

1157
01:21:20,642 --> 01:21:23,778
<i>The Japanese have been using</i>
<i>the same code for a year.</i>

1158
01:21:23,812 --> 01:21:27,082
<i>They have no reason</i>
<i>to suspect that</i>
<i>the Allies might break it.</i>

1159
01:21:27,115 --> 01:21:29,718
 <i>But a year is</i>
 <i>a long life for a code.</i>

1160
01:21:29,751 --> 01:21:31,353
(SPEAKS JAPANESE)

1161
01:21:36,324 --> 01:21:39,694
<i>Yamamoto thinks</i>
<i>it might be wise to change.</i>

1162
01:21:41,630 --> 01:21:44,132
<i>Kobe says there is not</i>
<i>enough time before the attack</i>

1163
01:21:44,165 --> 01:21:47,736
<i>to distribute new code books</i>
<i>to all levels of command.</i>

1164
01:21:47,769 --> 01:21:50,405
 <i>Yamamoto's thought</i>
 <i>was just a passing one.</i>

1165
01:21:50,438 --> 01:21:52,674
<i>The code will not be changed.</i>

1166
01:21:56,511 --> 01:21:57,846
<i>9 November,</i>

1167
01:21:57,879 --> 01:22:00,282
<i>Admiral Halsey rushes</i>
<i>more troop reinforcements</i>

1168
01:22:00,315 --> 01:22:02,417
<i>and supplies</i>
<i>toward Guadalcanal,</i>

1169
01:22:02,450 --> 01:22:04,452
<i>under the slim protection</i>
<i>of a small force</i>

1170
01:22:04,486 --> 01:22:07,088
<i>commanded by</i>
<i>Admiral Kelly Turner.</i>

1171
01:22:07,122 --> 01:22:09,457
<i>The question</i>
<i>in everyone's mind,</i>

1172
01:22:09,491 --> 01:22:11,593
<i>would these men</i>
<i>or these supplies,</i>

1173
01:22:11,626 --> 01:22:14,462
<i>standing naked</i>
<i>off the beaches, ever land?</i>

1174
01:22:18,233 --> 01:22:21,303
Well, pull up
some chairs
and let's get to it.

1175
01:22:29,644 --> 01:22:33,281
Well, sir,
according to all
available information,

1176
01:22:33,315 --> 01:22:36,318
the situation on
Zero Day,
11th November,

1177
01:22:37,152 --> 01:22:39,187
should shape up
as follows.

1178
01:22:39,220 --> 01:22:42,958
Kelly Turner's transports
should be finished
unloading by nightfall.

1179
01:22:42,991 --> 01:22:44,959
That will free
his escort
to move here

1180
01:22:44,993 --> 01:22:48,463
South of Savo Island,
to reinforce
Scott and Callaghan

1181
01:22:48,496 --> 01:22:51,399
if a night action
should develop.

1182
01:22:51,433 --> 01:22:55,670
Callaghan's cruiser force
and Scott's cruiser force
will be here.

1183
01:22:57,005 --> 01:23:00,842
Kincaid's force
of battleships
and heavy cruisers

1184
01:23:00,875 --> 01:23:04,045
will have escorted
the
<i>Enterprise</i>
 to within
flying range of the enemy,

1185
01:23:04,079 --> 01:23:06,314
about a hundred
or so miles
to the south,

1186
01:23:06,348 --> 01:23:09,217
depending on
when the
<i>Enterprise</i>
is ready to sail.

1187
01:23:09,250 --> 01:23:11,486
I just talked to Bailey,
sir.

1188
01:23:11,519 --> 01:23:13,054
Repairs on
the
<i>Enterprise</i>
 definitely

1189
01:23:13,088 --> 01:23:15,256
will not be
completed on time.

1190
01:23:15,290 --> 01:23:17,492
Then she'll have to
sail as is.

1191
01:23:17,525 --> 01:23:19,027
Half a carrier
is better than none.

1192
01:23:19,060 --> 01:23:21,363
HARRY: Admiral,

1193
01:23:21,396 --> 01:23:23,498
Frank has been going
round and round
with me on this,

1194
01:23:23,531 --> 01:23:26,735
he feels very
strongly that...
Sir...

1195
01:23:26,768 --> 01:23:28,870
Is the plan still open
for discussion?

1196
01:23:28,903 --> 01:23:29,938
Certainly.

1197
01:23:29,971 --> 01:23:33,041
Sir, following
the last engagement,

1198
01:23:33,074 --> 01:23:37,212
you correctly estimated
that their fleet
would withdraw.

1199
01:23:37,245 --> 01:23:40,749
The rest of us were
a little wrong
about that one.

1200
01:23:40,782 --> 01:23:43,551
This time we know
they're coming all the way.

1201
01:23:43,585 --> 01:23:45,420
And if we lose this one,

1202
01:23:45,453 --> 01:23:48,356
Guadalcanal is going
to be another Bataan.

1203
01:23:48,390 --> 01:23:51,459
Impossible to reinforce,
impossible to relieve.

1204
01:23:52,894 --> 01:23:55,730
Vandergrift will wind up
another Wainwright.

1205
01:23:56,598 --> 01:23:58,032
If we lose.

1206
01:23:58,066 --> 01:24:00,468
Well, before we send
Callaghan and Scott

1207
01:24:00,502 --> 01:24:02,871
into those narrow waters,
Admiral,

1208
01:24:02,904 --> 01:24:04,939
let's see what we've got.

1209
01:24:04,973 --> 01:24:07,742
Three cruisers,
a handful of destroyers.

1210
01:24:09,077 --> 01:24:10,645
Now, let's take a look at
what they've got.

1211
01:24:10,678 --> 01:24:14,048
The latest estimate
shows that they'll
have four battleships,

1212
01:24:14,082 --> 01:24:16,484
five heavy cruisers,
two carriers,

1213
01:24:16,518 --> 01:24:19,487
and about
30 destroyers.

1214
01:24:19,521 --> 01:24:21,589
The least we can do
is detach Lee's battleships

1215
01:24:21,623 --> 01:24:24,159
from the
<i>Enterprise</i>
 and
send them on ahead to help.

1216
01:24:24,192 --> 01:24:27,228
The battleships will have to
protect our one carrier

1217
01:24:27,262 --> 01:24:29,798
till she gets within range.

1218
01:24:29,831 --> 01:24:31,099
I may detach them later.

1219
01:24:31,132 --> 01:24:34,569
Well, sir, how long can three
cruisers and a few destroyers

1220
01:24:34,602 --> 01:24:37,338
delay a force
more than twice their size?

1221
01:24:38,139 --> 01:24:41,409
Dan Callaghan
and Norm Scott...

1222
01:24:41,443 --> 01:24:42,744
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1223
01:24:42,777 --> 01:24:44,012
Come in.

1224
01:24:46,781 --> 01:24:49,984
Admiral Callaghan
and Admiral Scott
are here, sir.

1225
01:24:53,822 --> 01:24:55,957
Send them in.
Aye, aye, sir.

1226
01:25:00,728 --> 01:25:03,898
Good evening, sir.
Dan. Norm.

1227
01:25:04,899 --> 01:25:07,102
You know
Harry Black?

1228
01:25:07,135 --> 01:25:08,770
Frank Enright.
Gentlemen.

1229
01:25:08,803 --> 01:25:11,172
Mike Pulaski.
How are you,
gentlemen?

1230
01:25:11,206 --> 01:25:13,641
I won't
keep you long.

1231
01:25:13,675 --> 01:25:16,845
I just wanted to
wish you good luck
before you shoved off.

1232
01:25:16,878 --> 01:25:19,881
We'll probably need
a little luck, sir.

1233
01:25:19,914 --> 01:25:21,916
Looks like
a real brawl.

1234
01:25:23,017 --> 01:25:25,286
I wish I could
change places
with you two.

1235
01:25:25,320 --> 01:25:27,555
We know you do,
sir.

1236
01:25:27,589 --> 01:25:29,724
I don't look for
a carrier action this time.

1237
01:25:29,757 --> 01:25:32,026
I think it'll be
a surface battle.

1238
01:25:32,060 --> 01:25:33,328
Guns and torpedoes.

1239
01:25:33,361 --> 01:25:36,464
Like Norm said,
a brawl.

1240
01:25:36,498 --> 01:25:39,734
And you can count on a real
loud rooting section up there.

1241
01:25:39,767 --> 01:25:42,003
Archie Vandergrift
and his Gyrenes.

1242
01:25:42,036 --> 01:25:45,406
Sir, we can't promise
Archie the Jap fleet
won't get through.

1243
01:25:45,440 --> 01:25:47,809
But if it does,
Norm and I guarantee

1244
01:25:47,842 --> 01:25:51,079
there won't be much left
afloat behind it.

1245
01:25:51,112 --> 01:25:53,581
Is that what you
had in mind, sir?

1246
01:25:54,682 --> 01:25:57,619
All I know is,
the job is in the right hands.

1247
01:25:58,419 --> 01:25:59,954
Thank you, sir.

1248
01:26:01,456 --> 01:26:02,690
BLACK: Goodbye, sir.
ENRIGHT: Good luck.

1249
01:26:02,724 --> 01:26:05,059
Good luck.
Goodnight, gentlemen.

1250
01:26:08,396 --> 01:26:10,198
Captain Black, sir?

1251
01:26:12,867 --> 01:26:14,102
No word?

1252
01:26:16,871 --> 01:26:18,139
No word.

1253
01:26:25,547 --> 01:26:29,017
Sir, there's something
I better tell you.

1254
01:26:29,050 --> 01:26:33,621
We've been waiting
for word on a float plane
overdue on a hop to Efate.

1255
01:26:37,325 --> 01:26:39,894
Your son is one
of the passengers.

1256
01:26:56,578 --> 01:26:59,480
HARRY: I'm going to
set up a special search.

1257
01:26:59,781 --> 01:27:02,016
No, no.

1258
01:27:04,018 --> 01:27:06,454
You will conduct
a routine search.

1259
01:27:07,755 --> 01:27:10,458
Thorough, but routine.

1260
01:27:11,092 --> 01:27:12,927
HARRY: Very well, sir.

1261
01:27:20,668 --> 01:27:22,737
<i>NARRATOR: 1,500 miles</i>
<i>to the northwest,</i>

1262
01:27:22,770 --> 01:27:26,140
<i>Admiral Yamamoto</i>
<i>moved his headquarters</i>
<i>from Truk to Rabaul,</i>

1263
01:27:26,174 --> 01:27:30,612
<i>in order to exercise</i>
<i>closer personal command</i>
<i>of the coming offensive.</i>

1264
01:27:36,684 --> 01:27:38,586
<i>Admiral Halsey's visit</i>
<i>to Guadalcanal</i>

1265
01:27:38,620 --> 01:27:41,289
<i>inspired his men there</i>
<i>to greater effort.</i>

1266
01:27:41,322 --> 01:27:43,958
<i>Yamamoto decides</i>
<i>on the same prescription,</i>

1267
01:27:43,992 --> 01:27:47,462
 <i>he will visit the most forward</i>
 <i>combat areas personally.</i>

1268
01:27:47,495 --> 01:27:50,865
 <i>Kobe opposes the plan</i>
 <i>but can't dissuade him.</i>

1269
01:27:50,898 --> 01:27:54,535
<i>As a safety measure,</i>
<i>Kobe suggests</i>
<i>Yamamoto wear the uniform</i>

1270
01:27:54,569 --> 01:27:57,271
<i>of a lower</i>
<i>and less conspicuous rank.</i>

1271
01:27:57,305 --> 01:27:59,641
<i>Admiral Yamamoto refuses.</i>

1272
01:27:59,674 --> 01:28:02,710
 <i>He will leave for Bougainville</i>
 <i>in the morning.</i>

1273
01:28:04,646 --> 01:28:07,649
<i>At a Japanese seaplane base</i>
<i>in the forward area,</i>

1274
01:28:07,682 --> 01:28:09,784
<i>a well intentioned</i>
<i>officer jeopardizes</i>

1275
01:28:09,817 --> 01:28:13,454
<i>the closely guarded secret of</i>
<i>Admiral Yamamoto's itinerary</i>

1276
01:28:13,488 --> 01:28:16,824
 <i>by alerting his local</i>
 <i>commanders in Naval code</i>

1277
01:28:16,858 --> 01:28:20,161
<i>to the impending visit</i>
<i>of their commander-in-chief.</i>

1278
01:28:23,998 --> 01:28:28,569
<i>The message is intercepted</i>
<i>and forwarded to Pearl Harbor</i>
<i>and Washington</i>

1279
01:28:28,603 --> 01:28:31,439
<i>for analysis</i>
<i>by American decoding experts.</i>

1280
01:29:34,435 --> 01:29:36,304
<i>(SONAR PINGING)</i>

1281
01:29:40,842 --> 01:29:43,778
 <i>MALE VOICE: (DISTORTED)</i>
 <i>Right on course 257.</i>

1282
01:29:44,445 --> 01:29:45,947
<i>MAN 2: Steady on 257.</i>

1283
01:29:47,582 --> 01:29:49,350
<i>MAN 3: Right, on course 257.</i>

1284
01:29:50,184 --> 01:29:51,919
<i>MAN 4: Right 257.</i>

1285
01:29:53,588 --> 01:29:55,757
<i>Steady on course 257.</i>

1286
01:29:56,824 --> 01:30:00,161
<i>MAN 5: Right 257.</i>

1287
01:30:00,194 --> 01:30:01,596
<i>MAN 2: Course 257.</i>

1288
01:30:02,663 --> 01:30:04,465
<i>Steady on course 257.</i>

1289
01:30:05,633 --> 01:30:08,469
<i>Covering course 257.</i>

1290
01:30:08,503 --> 01:30:10,705
<i>MAN 4: 257, aye.</i>

1291
01:30:11,839 --> 01:30:14,409
<i>Steady on course 257.</i>

