Good morning.

1433
01:41:01,255 --> 01:41:04,992
May I offer my
personal condolences, sir,

1434
01:41:06,326 --> 01:41:10,297
on the deaths
of Admiral Scott,
Admiral Callaghan?

1435
01:41:10,330 --> 01:41:11,732
I know how close
they were to you,

1436
01:41:11,765 --> 01:41:14,802
and how much their
friendship meant to you.

1437
01:41:14,835 --> 01:41:16,470
Thank you, Harry.

1438
01:41:17,604 --> 01:41:20,674
I have a dispatch here
from General Vandergrift.

1439
01:41:21,208 --> 01:41:22,509
Read it.

1440
01:41:22,543 --> 01:41:26,747
"To Scott, Callaghan
and their men
goes our greatest homage.

1441
01:41:26,780 --> 01:41:30,250
"With magnificent courage
against seemingly
hopeless odds,

1442
01:41:30,284 --> 01:41:34,721
"they drove back
the hostile stroke
and made success possible.

1443
01:41:35,656 --> 01:41:39,593
"To them
the men of Guadalcanal

1444
01:41:39,626 --> 01:41:44,298
"lift their battered helmets
in deepest admiration."

1445
01:41:47,067 --> 01:41:50,804
That was nice
of Archie, very nice.

1446
01:41:51,405 --> 01:41:52,706
Yes, sir.

1447
01:41:53,474 --> 01:41:55,843
There's another
dispatch, sir.

1448
01:41:55,876 --> 01:41:57,144
Read it.

1449
01:41:57,744 --> 01:41:59,513
It's personal, sir.

1450
01:42:10,257 --> 01:42:11,792
They found him.
Yes, sir.

1451
01:42:11,825 --> 01:42:16,163
Coast Watchers located
your son and his crew
early this morning.

1452
01:42:16,196 --> 01:42:18,532
They're all well?
All well, sir.

1453
01:42:19,666 --> 01:42:21,368
I was just about
to write Mrs. Halsey.

1454
01:42:21,401 --> 01:42:23,871
I understand, sir.
I'm a lucky man.

1455
01:42:23,904 --> 01:42:27,007
Yes, sir. And the day
is still very young, sir.

1456
01:42:28,041 --> 01:42:29,543
Just one more.

1457
01:42:33,614 --> 01:42:36,483
They're giving me
another star.

1458
01:42:36,517 --> 01:42:38,652
Sets of four stars
are in short supply,
hereabouts, sir.

1459
01:42:38,685 --> 01:42:41,855
I had a machinist mate
fix up a homemade pair.

1460
01:42:43,190 --> 01:42:45,659
A machinist mate?
Yes, sir.

1461
01:42:45,692 --> 01:42:48,028
Well that's...
That's very nice.

1462
01:42:56,703 --> 01:43:00,340
Have we anybody from the staff
going back to the States soon?

1463
01:43:00,374 --> 01:43:03,443
Yes, I believe
Lieutenant Lockwood
is leaving tomorrow.

1464
01:43:04,044 --> 01:43:05,712
Tomorrow?
Yes, sir.

1465
01:43:08,916 --> 01:43:11,218
Will you ask him
to do me a favor?

1466
01:43:11,251 --> 01:43:12,920
What's that, sir?

1467
01:43:15,589 --> 01:43:19,059
Will you ask him
to deliver these
personally

1468
01:43:20,260 --> 01:43:22,296
to Dan Callaghan's
widow?

1469
01:43:22,796 --> 01:43:24,097
Yes, sir.

1470
01:43:25,332 --> 01:43:29,236
And these
to Norm Scott's widow,

1471
01:43:31,138 --> 01:43:33,240
with the message,

1472
01:43:33,273 --> 01:43:37,144
that their husbands
earned me my new stars.

1473
01:43:37,578 --> 01:43:38,946
Yes, sir.

1474
01:43:38,979 --> 01:43:42,115
May I add
my warmest
congratulations, Admiral?

1475
01:43:42,149 --> 01:43:46,386
Not only on the promotion,
but on the turn of events
at Guadalcanal.

1476
01:43:46,420 --> 01:43:49,723
Even Frank Enright thinks
we may have them licked.

1477
01:43:49,756 --> 01:43:51,291
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1478
01:44:01,435 --> 01:44:05,572
Yamamoto doesn't seem
to know
that he's licked.

1479
01:44:05,606 --> 01:44:09,409
The rest of their force
is continuing down
the Slot on schedule.

1480
01:44:09,443 --> 01:44:12,879
Herding 20 transports
loaded with
invasion troops.

1481
01:44:14,281 --> 01:44:16,850
According to the book,
we don't send battleships

1482
01:44:16,883 --> 01:44:20,320
into waters
as narrow as those,
especially at night.

1483
01:44:20,354 --> 01:44:23,657
Forget the book?
Forget the book.

1484
01:44:23,690 --> 01:44:26,259
Detach Admiral Lee's
force from the
<i>Enterprise</i>
and send it ahead tonight.

1485
01:44:26,293 --> 01:44:27,427
Yes, sir.

1486
01:44:27,461 --> 01:44:28,962
HALSEY: The
<i>Enterprise</i>
planes can
follow up tomorrow.

1487
01:44:28,996 --> 01:44:30,297
Yes, sir.

1488
01:44:32,165 --> 01:44:34,001
May I see the Admiral?

1489
01:44:34,034 --> 01:44:35,702
What is it, Mike?

1490
01:44:47,080 --> 01:44:48,315
We've broken
the Jap code.

1491
01:44:48,348 --> 01:44:51,284
Yes, sir.
That was intercepted
from the Shortlands area.

1492
01:44:51,318 --> 01:44:54,321
Yamamoto's plane
is due to land
at the Jap air base in Kahili

1493
01:44:54,354 --> 01:44:56,556
at 11:35 on the 18th.

1494
01:44:56,590 --> 01:44:58,959
We've hit the Jackpot.
You think so?

1495
01:44:58,992 --> 01:45:01,528
Admiral, this was
made to order.

1496
01:45:01,561 --> 01:45:03,463
That's what bothers me.

1497
01:45:03,497 --> 01:45:06,266
HARRY: Admiral Lee
has been notified, sir.

1498
01:45:08,435 --> 01:45:09,536
A chance to
get Yamamoto.

1499
01:45:09,569 --> 01:45:12,205
Not only Yamamoto
but his whole Staff.

1500
01:45:14,207 --> 01:45:16,643
About 750 miles.

1501
01:45:16,677 --> 01:45:17,911
That's out of range
for anything we've got,

1502
01:45:17,944 --> 01:45:20,347
but the Army P-38's
could make it.

1503
01:45:22,683 --> 01:45:26,420
We break the Jap code
at just the right minute.

1504
01:45:28,522 --> 01:45:33,694
Then this message falls
into our lap
at just the right minute.

1505
01:45:37,631 --> 01:45:39,700
How do we know
this isn't a trap?

1506
01:45:39,733 --> 01:45:41,268
We don't, sir.

1507
01:45:42,202 --> 01:45:45,338
On the other hand,
if it is a trap,

1508
01:45:45,372 --> 01:45:48,709
wouldn't they go
about it a little
more subtly?

1509
01:45:48,742 --> 01:45:51,378
Washington leaves that
up to you, sir.

1510
01:45:52,479 --> 01:45:54,948
Advise
Archie Vandergrift
and Geiger

1511
01:45:54,981 --> 01:45:56,516
I'm leaving
for Guadalcanal now.

1512
01:45:56,550 --> 01:45:57,884
Yes, sir.

1513
01:46:03,724 --> 01:46:05,392
(SIRENS BLARING)

1514
01:46:22,175 --> 01:46:26,079
I see no point,
none at all in
speculating about a trap.

1515
