If Yamamoto
doesn't show,

1516
01:46:29,149 --> 01:46:32,819
the P-38's will refuse
combat and hightail it.

1517
01:46:32,853 --> 01:46:36,289
The question is,
what's the best
plan of attack?

1518
01:46:36,323 --> 01:46:39,226
Well, sir, I don't think
that we should try
to get him in the air.

1519
01:46:39,259 --> 01:46:41,461
There's too many variables,
the weather conditions,

1520
01:46:41,495 --> 01:46:43,997
he may be late,
he may be early,
we might miss him.

1521
01:46:44,030 --> 01:46:45,332
How would you do it,
Andy?

1522
01:46:45,365 --> 01:46:47,234
Well, hit him
when he's most vulnerable.

1523
01:46:47,267 --> 01:46:49,002
After he's landed
on Ballale island,

1524
01:46:49,035 --> 01:46:53,340
he's scheduled
to take a sub chaser
from there to Buin.

1525
01:46:53,373 --> 01:46:56,376
ANDY: I say strafe him
when he's on the water.

1526
01:46:57,310 --> 01:47:00,080
What do you say, Lamphier?

1527
01:47:00,113 --> 01:47:04,184
Oh. Well,
no pun intended, sir,

1528
01:47:04,217 --> 01:47:06,987
but I think
that approach is all wet.

1529
01:47:07,020 --> 01:47:08,955
Could you be a little bit
more explicit, Captain?

1530
01:47:08,989 --> 01:47:10,924
Sure.

1531
01:47:10,957 --> 01:47:14,995
Now Army pilot's
are gonna carry the ball
in this thing, correct?

1532
01:47:15,028 --> 01:47:16,930
Well, I hate to
embarrass anybody,

1533
01:47:16,963 --> 01:47:19,966
but the plain fact is
that Army pilots,
including yours,

1534
01:47:20,000 --> 01:47:22,936
truly, are not so hot
on Naval identification.

1535
01:47:22,969 --> 01:47:25,939
Based on past performance
I'd say there's
a strong possibility

1536
01:47:25,972 --> 01:47:29,009
that we might
pick out something else
instead of the sub chaser.

1537
01:47:29,042 --> 01:47:30,944
Oh, now looky here...

1538
01:47:30,977 --> 01:47:32,646
I'm not through.

1539
01:47:33,680 --> 01:47:35,615
If we do strafe
the right boat,

1540
01:47:35,649 --> 01:47:39,352
we could miss Yamamoto,
or maybe just wound him.

1541
01:47:39,386 --> 01:47:42,956
And if we sink the boat,
what's the guarantee
that he won't swim away?

1542
01:47:42,989 --> 01:47:47,160
Well, there's no guarantee
that you're gonna get him
in the air, either.

1543
01:47:48,862 --> 01:47:52,632
Your way might work,
Andy, but...

1544
01:47:52,666 --> 01:47:56,670
I think the fellow
who has to do the job
should call the play.

1545
01:47:57,838 --> 01:48:00,006
We'll go for him in the air.

1546
01:48:06,446 --> 01:48:08,114
(PLANES HOVERING)

1547
01:48:27,434 --> 01:48:29,169
I counted
only 14, sir.

1548
01:48:29,202 --> 01:48:30,570
Must've been
some mechanical trouble.

1549
01:48:30,604 --> 01:48:33,406
Four of those P-38's
didn't get off.

1550
01:48:33,440 --> 01:48:35,508
18 was little enough.

1551
01:48:35,542 --> 01:48:37,777
Signal from
Admiral Lee, sir.

1552
01:48:40,280 --> 01:48:42,883
Lee's lost two destroyers,
but he sank the
<i>Kirishima.</i>

1553
01:48:42,916 --> 01:48:44,417
The Japs have
reversed course.

1554
01:48:44,451 --> 01:48:46,519
Sounds like our chance
for a field day.

1555
01:48:46,553 --> 01:48:48,255
And we're gonna
make the most of it.

1556
01:48:48,288 --> 01:48:49,456
Clear the decks at
daybreak and go after

1557
01:48:49,489 --> 01:48:50,857
those two transports.
Yes, sir.

1558
01:48:50,891 --> 01:48:52,759
I want your B-17Ts
in on this.
Yes, sir.

1559
01:48:52,792 --> 01:48:54,761
And notify
the
<i>Enterprise.</i>

1560
01:48:54,794 --> 01:48:55,862
I want her boys
in on this, too.

1561
01:48:55,896 --> 01:48:56,897
Yes, sir.

1562
01:49:03,436 --> 01:49:05,038
They're landing
and taking off again

1563
01:49:05,071 --> 01:49:07,641
as fast as they can
rearm and refuel.

1564
01:49:08,742 --> 01:49:10,911
It's becoming
a shuttle run.

1565
01:49:12,245 --> 01:49:15,649
The Jap escorts
are abandoning
the troop ships.

1566
01:49:15,682 --> 01:49:19,586
Well, from here on end
it'll be like shooting
fish in a barrel.

1567
01:49:20,120 --> 01:49:22,088
Keep pouring it on.

1568
01:49:22,122 --> 01:49:23,423
Yes, sir.

1569
01:49:24,257 --> 01:49:25,358
Roy.

1570
01:49:26,593 --> 01:49:28,194
General Geiger.

1571
01:49:29,529 --> 01:49:31,264
Sir?

1572
01:49:31,298 --> 01:49:33,733
Any word on the
Yamamoto thing?

1573
01:49:33,767 --> 01:49:35,268
Not yet, sir.

1574
01:49:39,005 --> 01:49:41,641
If Yamamoto was
on schedule,

1575
01:49:41,675 --> 01:49:44,010
they should have
intercepted him at 9:50.

1576
01:49:44,044 --> 01:49:47,314
That was
40 minutes ago.

1577
01:49:48,615 --> 01:49:49,916
They'll have
to get well
out of the area

1578
01:49:49,950 --> 01:49:53,587
before they can break
radio silence
and report, Admiral.

1579
01:49:53,620 --> 01:49:56,456
I think it's
still a little
early for that.

1580
01:49:57,457 --> 01:50:00,193
Another flight back
from the transports.

1581
01:50:03,029 --> 01:50:04,664
(PLANE WHIRRING)

1582
01:50:37,163 --> 01:50:38,331
Andy?

1583
01:50:45,205 --> 01:50:46,973
How is it?

1584
01:50:47,007 --> 01:50:49,909
Oh, we're rolling up
a big score.

1585
01:50:52,846 --> 01:50:56,616
Any word from
that bunch that you
sent after Yamamoto?

1586
01:50:57,217 --> 01:50:58,518
Not yet.

1587
01:50:59,786 --> 01:51:03,890
Andy, how many runs have you
made over those transports?

1588
01:51:05,025 --> 01:51:08,395
This next one
will be my fourth.

1589
01:51:13,900 --> 01:51:15,435
(ALL CHEERING)

1590
01:51:15,468 --> 01:51:17,771
They got him, sir!
They got him!

1591
01:51:18,772 --> 01:51:22,008
Tom Lamphier got Yamamoto.
A confirmed kill.

1592
01:51:22,042 --> 01:51:25,111
Rex Barber splashed
the other Betty
carrying Yamamoto's staff.

1593
01:51:25,145 --> 01:51:28,681
Both aircraft.
Good works, Admiral,
a complete success.

1594
01:51:28,715 --> 01:51:30,283
(MARINES CHEER)

1595
01:51:32,052 --> 01:51:33,753
What were our losses?

1596
01:51:33,787 --> 01:51:35,555
Four aircraft, sir.

1597
01:51:41,428 --> 01:51:43,096
(EXCITED CHATTER)

1598
01:52:03,316 --> 01:52:04,851
How do I look?

1599
01:52:06,853 --> 01:52:08,321
Unusual, sir.

1600
01:52:10,957 --> 01:52:13,159
Well, I guess I better
get it over with.

1601
01:52:13,193 --> 01:52:14,494
Yes, sir.

1602
01:52:30,310 --> 01:52:32,545
Goodbye, Manuel.
Goodbye, sir.

1603
01:53:45,185 --> 01:53:46,819
Request permission
to leave the ship.

1604
01:53:46,853 --> 01:53:49,055
Request granted.
Hand salute.

1605
01:53:50,723 --> 01:53:52,292
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

1606
01:54:57,924 --> 01:55:02,795
<i>♪ I knew a lad who went to sea</i>

1607
01:55:02,829 --> 01:55:08,735
<i>♪ And left the shore</i>
<i>behind him</i>

1608
01:55:08,768 --> 01:55:15,141
<i>♪ I knew him well</i>
<i>the lad was me</i>

1609
01:55:15,174 --> 01:55:22,115
<i>♪ And now I cannot find him </i>

1610
01:55:23,950 --> 01:55:27,954
<i>NARRATOR: There are no</i>
<i>great men. There are only</i>
<i>great challenges</i>

1611
01:55:27,987 --> 01:55:32,325
<i>that ordinary men are forced</i>
<i>by circumstances to meet.</i>

